{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784180560354,"sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_a9905f74a179428d9c37d7a7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/010-scorecard-and-closeout/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/010-scorecard-and-closeout/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Feature Specification: scorecard and closeout — two-axis scorecard, remediation backlog, and packet reconciliation\"\n3: description: \"Publishes the two-axis scorecard and remediation backlog, reconciles all packet status metadata, and runs recursive strict validation so the benchmark ships as a coherent, evidence-backed packet.\"\n4: status: planned\n5: trigger_phrases:\n6:   - \"command benchmark scorecard\"\n7:   - \"two-axis scorecard\"\n8:   - \"remediation backlog\"\n9:   - \"packet closeout\"\n10: importance_tier: \"important\"\n11: contextType: \"planning\"\n12: _memory:\n13:   continuity:\n14:     packet_pointer: \"system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/010-scorecard-and-closeout\"\n15:     last_updated_at: \"2026-07-14T20:45:00Z\"\n16:     last_updated_by: \"claude\"\n17:     recent_action: \"Scaffolded the closeout child that publishes the two-axis scorecard\"\n18:     next_safe_action: \"Compile the deterministic and behavioral axes into the scorecard\"\n19:     blockers: []\n20:     key_files:\n21:       - \".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/shared/behavior-benchmark/framework.md\"\n22:       - \".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-alignment/scripts/scoping.cjs\"\n23:     open_questions: []\n24:     answered_questions: []\n25: ---\n26: <!-- SPECKIT_TEMPLATE_SOURCE: spec-core | v2.2 -->\n27: \n28: <!-- SPECKIT_LEVEL: 1 -->\n29: \n30: # Feature Specification: scorecard and closeout — two-axis scorecard, remediation backlog, and packet reconciliation\n31: \n32: <!-- ANCHOR:metadata -->\n33: ## 1. METADATA\n34: \n35: | Field | Value |\n36: |-------|-------|\n37: | **Level** | 1 |\n38: | **Priority** | P1 |\n39: | **Status** | Planned |\n40: | **Created** | 2026-07-14 |\n41: | **Parent Spec** | ../spec.md |\n42: <!-- /ANCHOR:metadata -->\n43: \n44: <!-- ANCHOR:problem -->\n45: ## 2. PROBLEM & PURPOSE\n46: \n47: The benchmark produces two independent verdicts and a matrix; it needs a single coherent closeout. This phase publishes a two-axis scorecard and a remediation backlog, reconciles packet status metadata, and runs recursive strict validation, keeping instrument validity and command conformance as separate claims.\n48: <!-- /ANCHOR:problem -->\n49: \n50: <!-- ANCHOR:scope -->\n51: ## 3. SCOPE\n52: \n53: **In scope:**\n54: - Publish a two-axis scorecard that never averages the deterministic and behavioral axes.\n55: - Publish a remediation backlog for failing commands as downstream planning input.\n56: - Reconcile all packet status metadata across spec, graph, and description surfaces.\n57: - Run recursive strict validation over the whole packet.\n58: - Gate the new `conformance_benchmark` family, the `/deep:command-benchmark` command and its generated Codex mirror, the final 37-command census equality, command-reference validation, and adapter/reducer agreement at closeout.\n59: \n60: **Out of scope:**\n61: - Remediating any command the benchmark measures as failing.\n62: - Changing scoring or scenario contracts.\n63: <!-- /ANCHOR:scope -->\n64: \n65: <!-- ANCHOR:requirements -->\n66: ## 4. REQUIREMENTS\n67: \n68: - **REQ-001 (P0):** Publish a two-axis scorecard that keeps deterministic P-level and behavioral D-level results non-averaged.\n69: - **REQ-002 (P0):** Recursive strict validation over the packet exits 0.\n70: - **REQ-003 (P1):** Publish a remediation backlog and keep instrument validity separate from command conformance.\n71: - **REQ-004 (P1):** Reconcile packet status metadata across map, graph, checklist, summaries, and scorecard.\n72: - **REQ-005 (P2):** Keep existing command-reference and prompt-sync gates green at closeout.\n73: - **REQ-006 (P1):** Closeout gates pass for the new family, the command and generated mirror, the final 37-command census equality, command-reference validation, adapter/reducer agreement, and separate deterministic and behavioral scorecard sections.\n74: <!-- /ANCHOR:requirements -->\n75: \n76: <!-- ANCHOR:success-criteria -->\n77: ## 5. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n78: \n79: - The two-axis scorecard is published with non-averaged axes.\n80: - Recursive strict validation exits 0.\n81: - Existing reference and sync gates remain green.\n82: - Map, graph, checklist, summaries, and scorecard agree.\n83: - The final 37-command census reconciles, and the new family, command, and generated mirror pass their closeout gates.\n84: <!-- /ANCHOR:success-criteria -->\n85: \n86: <!-- ANCHOR:risks -->\n87: ## 6. RISKS & DEPENDENCIES\n88: \n89: - Metadata drift across surfaces, mitigated by a reconciliation pass before validation.\n90: - Conflating instrument validity with command conformance, mitigated by separate reported claims.\n91: - Dependencies: all prior phase outputs.\n92: <!-- /ANCHOR:risks -->\n93: \n94: <!-- ANCHOR:questions -->\n95: ## 7. OPEN QUESTIONS\n96: \n97: - Whether the remediation backlog should be a separate packet or a section handed to planning.\n98: <!-- /ANCHOR:questions -->\n99: \n100: ## PHASE SEQUENCE\n101: \n102: Predecessor: 009-command-benchmark-command. Successor: packet closeout.\n\n(End of file - total 102 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Feature Specification: scorecard and closeout — two-axis scorecard, remediation backlog, and packet reconciliation\"\ndescription: \"Publishes the two-axis scorecard and remediation backlog, reconciles all packet status metadata, and runs recursive strict validation so the benchmark ships as a coherent, evidence-backed packet.\"\nstatus: planned\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"command benchmark scorecard\"\n  - \"two-axis scorecard\"\n  - \"remediation backlog\"\n  - \"packet closeout\"\nimportance_tier: \"important\"\ncontextType: \"planning\"\n_memory:\n  continuity:\n    packet_pointer: \"system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/010-scorecard-and-closeout\"\n    last_updated_at: \"2026-07-14T20:45:00Z\"\n    last_updated_by: \"claude\"\n    recent_action: \"Scaffolded the closeout child that publishes the two-axis scorecard\"\n    next_safe_action: \"Compile the deterministic and behavioral axes into the scorecard\"\n    blockers: []\n    key_files:","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/010-scorecard-and-closeout/spec.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Feature Specification: scorecard and closeout — two-axis scorecard, remediation backlog, and packet reconciliation\"\ndescription: \"Publishes the two-axis scorecard and remediation backlog, reconciles all packet status metadata, and runs recursive strict validation so the benchmark ships as a coherent, evidence-backed packet.\"\nstatus: planned\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"command benchmark scorecard\"\n  - \"two-axis scorecard\"\n  - \"remediation backlog\"\n  - \"packet closeout\"\nimportance_tier: \"important\"\ncontextType: \"planning\"\n_memory:\n  continuity:\n    packet_pointer: \"system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/010-scorecard-and-closeout\"\n    last_updated_at: \"2026-07-14T20:45:00Z\"\n    last_updated_by: \"claude\"\n    recent_action: \"Scaffolded the closeout child that publishes the two-axis scorecard\"\n    next_safe_action: \"Compile the deterministic and behavioral axes into the scorecard\"\n    blockers: []\n    key_files:\n      - \".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/shared/behavior-benchmark/framework.md\"\n      - \".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-alignment/scripts/scoping.cjs\"\n    open_questions: []\n    answered_questions: []\n---\n<!-- SPECKIT_TEMPLATE_SOURCE: spec-core | v2.2 -->\n\n<!-- SPECKIT_LEVEL: 1 -->\n\n# Feature Specification: scorecard and closeout — two-axis scorecard, remediation backlog, and packet reconciliation\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:metadata -->\n## 1. METADATA\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| **Level** | 1 |\n| **Priority** | P1 |\n| **Status** | Planned |\n| **Created** | 2026-07-14 |\n| **Parent Spec** | ../spec.md |\n<!-- /ANCHOR:metadata -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:problem -->\n## 2. PROBLEM & PURPOSE\n\nThe benchmark produces two independent verdicts and a matrix; it needs a single coherent closeout. This phase publishes a two-axis scorecard and a remediation backlog, reconciles packet status metadata, and runs recursive strict validation, keeping instrument validity and command conformance as separate claims.\n<!-- /ANCHOR:problem -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:scope -->\n## 3. SCOPE\n\n**In scope:**\n- Publish a two-axis scorecard that never averages the deterministic and behavioral axes.\n- Publish a remediation backlog for failing commands as downstream planning input.\n- Reconcile all packet status metadata across spec, graph, and description surfaces.\n- Run recursive strict validation over the whole packet.\n- Gate the new `conformance_benchmark` family, the `/deep:command-benchmark` command and its generated Codex mirror, the final 37-command census equality, command-reference validation, and adapter/reducer agreement at closeout.\n\n**Out of scope:**\n- Remediating any command the benchmark measures as failing.\n- Changing scoring or scenario contracts.\n<!-- /ANCHOR:scope -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:requirements -->\n## 4. REQUIREMENTS\n\n- **REQ-001 (P0):** Publish a two-axis scorecard that keeps deterministic P-level and behavioral D-level results non-averaged.\n- **REQ-002 (P0):** Recursive strict validation over the packet exits 0.\n- **REQ-003 (P1):** Publish a remediation backlog and keep instrument validity separate from command conformance.\n- **REQ-004 (P1):** Reconcile packet status metadata across map, graph, checklist, summaries, and scorecard.\n- **REQ-005 (P2):** Keep existing command-reference and prompt-sync gates green at closeout.\n- **REQ-006 (P1):** Closeout gates pass for the new family, the command and generated mirror, the final 37-command census equality, command-reference validation, adapter/reducer agreement, and separate deterministic and behavioral scorecard sections.\n<!-- /ANCHOR:requirements -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:success-criteria -->\n## 5. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n\n- The two-axis scorecard is published with non-averaged axes.\n- Recursive strict validation exits 0.\n- Existing reference and sync gates remain green.\n- Map, graph, checklist, summaries, and scorecard agree.\n- The final 37-command census reconciles, and the new family, command, and generated mirror pass their closeout gates.\n<!-- /ANCHOR:success-criteria -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:risks -->\n## 6. RISKS & DEPENDENCIES\n\n- Metadata drift across surfaces, mitigated by a reconciliation pass before validation.\n- Conflating instrument validity with command conformance, mitigated by separate reported claims.\n- Dependencies: all prior phase outputs.\n<!-- /ANCHOR:risks -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:questions -->\n## 7. OPEN QUESTIONS\n\n- Whether the remediation backlog should be a separate packet or a section handed to planning.\n<!-- /ANCHOR:questions -->\n\n## PHASE SEQUENCE\n\nPredecessor: 009-command-benchmark-command. Successor: packet closeout.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":102,"totalLines":102,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/010-scorecard-and-closeout/spec.md","time":{"start":1784180560347,"end":1784180560351}},"id":"prt_f6972d1da001BLkoJC5iDr6THM","sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","messageID":"msg_f6972a67d001NDlWgKNP9yChdH"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784180560354,"sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_5ffee766c71d46a9b4175438","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/SKILL.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: create-command\n3: description: Scaffold OpenCode slash commands with explicit argument hints, allowed tools, and router/presentation separation.\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\n5: version: 1.0.1.1\n6: ---\n7: \n8: <!-- Keywords: create-command, slash command, opencode command, argument-hint, allowed-tools, command router, presentation contract, thin router, command scaffold -->\n9: \n10: # Create Command\n11: \n12: `create-command` is the command-authoring workflow packet of the `sk-doc` parent hub. It creates and improves OpenCode slash commands under `.opencode/commands/` with executable workflows, precise frontmatter, required input gates, least-privilege tools, and router/presentation separation when needed.\n13: \n14: This SKILL.md contains the core creation workflow. Use the `references/` route map (`references/README.md`), `assets/command_template.md`, `assets/command_router_template.md`, `assets/command_presentation_template.md`, and `../shared/` only for exhaustive examples, edge cases, and validator implementation detail.\n15: \n16: This packet is lean and self-contained. The advisor identity lives at the `sk-doc` hub root; do not add packet-local `graph-metadata.json`.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n21: \n22: ### Activation Triggers\n23: \n24: Use this packet when the request involves:\n25: \n26: - Creating a new OpenCode slash command.\n27: - Refactoring a command into a thin router plus owned presentation asset.\n28: - Adding or fixing command frontmatter, especially `argument-hint` and `allowed-tools`.\n29: - Designing command argument handling with `$ARGUMENTS`.\n30: - Authoring a namespace command such as `/namespace:action`.\n31: - Separating visible prompts, dashboards, result templates, or next-step wording into a presentation contract.\n32: - Checking whether a workflow should be a command instead of a skill, agent, or one-off task.\n33: \n34: Keyword triggers: `create command`, `/create:command`, `slash command`, `OpenCode command`, `argument-hint`, `allowed-tools`, `command template`, `router presentation split`, `thin router`, `presentation contract`, `$ARGUMENTS`.\n35: \n36: ### When NOT to Use\n37: \n38: Use another `sk-doc` packet when:\n39: \n40: - The request is to create a skill or parent hub. Use `create-skill`.\n41: - The request is to create an agent. Use `create-agent`.\n42: - The task is a README, install guide, feature catalog, manual testing playbook, benchmark package, flowchart, or changelog. Use `create-readme`, `create-feature-catalog`, `create-manual-testing-playbook`, `create-benchmark`, `create-flowchart`, or `create-changelog`.\n43: - The task audits, validates, scores, or optimizes an existing command document. Use `create-quality-control`.\n44: - The task is one-time work that does not need a reusable slash command.\n45: - The command already exists and the user only wants runtime debugging.\n46: - The requested workflow is destructive or externally privileged but lacks confirmation and rollback requirements.\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n51: \n52: These triggers route a request into this command-authoring packet. Execution-mode suffixes are command syntax, not packet-selection triggers. When the surface is a slash command, stay in this packet and continue to the creation workflow below.\n53: \n54: ### Router Resilience\n55: \n56: This packet routes by command-authoring intent and the requested component surface. It does not use runtime keyed resource discovery through `references/<key>/` because its references are flat.\n57: \n58: - Load optional markdown resources only after resolving them under this packet and confirming they exist.\n59: - Treat `references/README.md` as the fallback route map when command intent or component surface is unclear.\n60: - Ask for the missing command purpose, invocation shape, or component type instead of silently loading no resources.\n61: - Do not add a full `references/<key>/` or `assets/<key>/` runtime-key router unless this packet gains real keyed resource subdirectories.\n62: \n63: ### Resource Loading Sequence\n64: \n65: The packet keeps its existing flat-resource routing while using the shared resilience call sequence:\n66: \n67: ```python\n68: def discover_markdown_resources():\n69:     return flat markdown resources under this packet's `references/` and `assets/` folders\n70: \n71: def _guard_in_skill(relative_path):\n72:     # Keep packet-local markdown paths in scope; retain explicitly documented shared routes.\n73:     confirm the path is an allowed markdown resource for this packet\n74: \n75: def load_if_available(relative_path, inventory, seen):\n76:     guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n77:     if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n78:         load(guarded)\n79:         seen.add(guarded)\n80: \n81: def route_create_command_request(request):\n82:     inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n83:     intents = score_intents(request)  # command-authoring intent and component surface\n84:     selected = select_intents(intents)\n85:     routing_key = get_routing_key(request, selected)\n86:     if not selected or the command purpose or component surface is unclear:\n87:         load_if_available(\"references/README.md\", inventory, seen)\n88:         return UNKNOWN_FALLBACK\n89:     return route by the existing command-authoring intent and component-surface rules\n90: ```\n91: \n92: `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK` asks for the command purpose, invocation shape, or component type. The sequence discovers the current flat resources at routing time, guards and loads only available resources without duplicates, then applies the activation triggers and command-type rules already defined below.\n93: \n94: ---\n95: \n96: ## 3. HOW IT WORKS: CREATION WORKFLOW\n97: \n98: Follow these steps in order.\n99: \n100: ### Step 1: Decide Whether A Command Is Correct\n101: \n102: Create a command only when the workflow is repeatable and has defined steps.\n103: \n104: Use a command when the workflow:\n105: \n106: - Automates a multi-step process.\n107: - Needs repeatable execution across sessions.\n108: - Needs `$ARGUMENTS` parsing or mode routing.\n109: - Needs user-controlled execution pace such as `:auto` or `:confirm`.\n110: - Needs confirmation gates for destructive or privileged actions.\n111: - Benefits from explicit tool restrictions.\n112: \n113: Use a skill instead when the content is reusable reference knowledge, domain guidance, standards, or patterns shared by multiple workflows. Do not create a command for one-off work.\n114: \n115: ### Step 2: Resolve Invocation And Path\n116: \n117: Determine the command invocation before writing:\n118: \n119: - Root command: `.opencode/commands/<command>.md` becomes `/<command>`.\n120: - Namespace command: `.opencode/commands/<namespace>/<action>.md` becomes `/<namespace>:<action>`.\n121: - Namespace and action names use lowercase hyphen-case.\n122: \n123: For grouped related actions, prefer a namespace directory:\n124: \n125: ```text\n126: .opencode/commands/\n127: └── <namespace>/\n128:     ├── <action1>.md\n129:     ├── <action2>.md\n130:     └── <action3>.md\n131: ```\n132: \n133: ### Step 3: Read Existing Files First\n134: \n135: Before editing an existing command or owned asset, read it completely enough to understand current behavior. Preserve behavior unless the user explicitly asks to change it.\n136: \n137: For new commands, inspect nearby commands in the same namespace when available so structure and vocabulary match the command family.\n138: \n139: ### Step 4: Classify The Command Type\n140: \n141: Choose the smallest command type that fits:\n142: \n143: | Type | Use When | Typical Shape |\n144: | --- | --- | --- |\n145: | Simple | Single action, few arguments | One `.md` file, direct steps |\n146: | Workflow | Multi-step process with checkpoints | One `.md` file with overview, instructions, recovery |\n147: | Mode-based | Supports `:auto` / `:confirm` | Thin router plus owned assets when complex |\n148: | Router | Thin dispatcher: verify agent, resolve mode/args, hand off to owned assets | Router `.md` plus owned presentation `.txt` and optional workflow YAML or scripts |\n149: | Argument dispatch | Multiple action keywords or query forms | ASCII routing tree plus handlers |\n150: | Destructive | Deletes data or irreversible changes | Explicit confirmation, affected-state display, recovery guidance |\n151: | Namespace | Related commands grouped together | Directory under `.opencode/commands/` |\n152: \n153: If the command combines patterns, parse mode first, then dispatch remaining arguments.\n154: \n155: ### Step 5: Choose The Output Package Shape\n156: \n157: For a simple or medium command, create or update:\n158: \n159: ```text\n160: .opencode/commands/<command>.md\n161: ```\n162: \n163: For a namespace command, create or update:\n164: \n165: ```text\n166: .opencode/commands/<namespace>/<action>.md\n167: ```\n168: \n169: For a split mode-based workflow command, create or update:\n170: \n171: ```text\n172: .opencode/commands/<namespace>/<action>.md\n173: .opencode/commands/<namespace>/assets/<namespace>_<action>_presentation.txt\n174: .opencode/commands/<namespace>/assets/<namespace>_<action>_auto.yaml\n175: .opencode/commands/<namespace>/assets/<namespace>_<action>_confirm.yaml\n176: ```\n177: \n178: Use `_auto.yaml` and `_confirm.yaml` only for workflow-backed families that route execution into workflow assets. Direct-router families dispatch directly to tools/scripts and do not need workflow YAML.\n179: \n180: For a compiled-stub router, the `.md` is a generated thin stub carrying the `render-command-contract` marker; its section shape is rendered from a compiled source at invocation, not authored in the file. Do not hand-write section headings into a compiled stub, and keep its owned presentation/workflow assets alongside it:\n181: \n182: ```text\n183: .opencode/commands/<namespace>/<action>.md            # compiled stub (render-command-contract marker)\n184: .opencode/commands/<namespace>/assets/<namespace>_<action>_presentation.txt\n185: ```\n186: \n187: ### Step 6: Author Frontmatter First\n188: \n189: Every command starts with YAML frontmatter.\n190: \n191: Required:\n192: \n193: ```yaml\n194: ---\n195: description: Action-oriented single-line description\n196: ---\n197: ```\n198: \n199: Recommended when applicable:\n200: \n201: ```yaml\n202: argument-hint: \"<required> [optional] [--flag]\"\n203: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash\n204: ```\n205: \n206: Rules:\n207: \n208: - Keep `description` single-line, action-oriented, and concise.\n209: - Target descriptions at or under 110 characters.\n210: - Do not use YAML block scalars for `description`.\n211: - Use `argument-hint` whenever the command expects user input.\n212: - Use `<angle-brackets>` only for required arguments.\n213: - Use `[square-brackets]` for optional arguments.\n214: - List every tool the command actually uses in `allowed-tools`.\n215: - Do not add broad tools just in case.\n216: - For MCP tools in `allowed-tools`, use fully qualified names such as `mcp__<server>__<tool>`.\n217: - Bare tool names such as `memory_context` belong in prose only, not `allowed-tools`.\n218: \n219: ### Step 7: Add Mandatory Input Gates\n220: \n221: If `argument-hint` contains any required `<argument>`, add the mandatory gate immediately after frontmatter, before all other content.\n222: \n223: The gate must:\n224: \n225: - Check whether `$ARGUMENTS` is empty, undefined, or whitespace-only.\n226: - Ignore mode suffixes when determining whether required content exists.\n227: - Stop immediately when required input is missing.\n228: - Ask a context-specific question with clear options or expected reply format.\n229: - Wait for the user response.\n230: - Use only `$ARGUMENTS` or the user's explicit answer as the input.\n231: - Forbid inference from context, screenshots, conversation history, or open files.\n232: \n233: For multi-input commands, use a blocking phase pattern:\n234: \n235: - Phase 1: input collection.\n236: - Phase 2: prerequisite/context verification.\n237: - Phase status verification table.\n238: - Violation self-detection block.\n239: \n240: Every workflow command with blocking phases must include violation self-detection: if a required phase was skipped, stop, state the violation, return to the phase, and complete it properly.\n241: \n242: ### Step 8: Write The Command Body\n243: \n244: Use executable, instruction-oriented sections. Commands are workflows, not long reference manuals.\n245: \n246: Common section order:\n247: \n248: 1. Title and purpose.\n249: 2. Contract.\n250: 3. Workflow overview or argument routing.\n251: 4. Instructions.\n252: 5. Failure recovery and error handling when needed.\n253: 6. Examples.\n254: 7. Status output patterns or completion report.\n255: \n256: Use these conventions:\n257: \n258: - H1: plain command title, or a blocking semantic title for mandatory gates.\n259: - H2: `## N. SECTION-NAME`, using full integers only.\n260: - H3 steps: `### Step N: Description`.\n261: - Do not use decimal steps such as `1.5` or `2.5`.\n262: - Put sub-activities in bullets under a numbered step.\n263: - Use dividers between major sections when they improve scanability.\n264: - Return structured statuses such as `STATUS=OK`, `STATUS=FAIL ERROR=\"<message>\"`, or `STATUS=CANCELLED ACTION=cancelled`.\n265: \n266: Approved common H2 section names include:\n267: \n268: - `PURPOSE`\n269: - `CONTRACT`\n270: - `WORKFLOW OVERVIEW`\n271: - `INSTRUCTIONS`\n272: - `ARGUMENT ROUTING`\n273: - `REFERENCE`\n274: - `EXAMPLES`\n275: - `RELATED COMMANDS`\n276: - `TOOL SIGNATURES`\n277: - `USER INPUT`\n278: \n279: Approved canonical H2 section names for router commands (see Step 11):\n280: \n281: - `ROUTER CONTRACT`\n282: - `OWNED ASSETS`\n283: - `MODE ROUTING`\n284: - `EXECUTION TARGETS`\n285: - `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`\n286: - `WORKFLOW SUMMARY`\n287: \n288: ### Step 9: Implement Argument Dispatch When Needed\n289: \n290: For commands with multiple entry points, include an ASCII routing tree based on `$ARGUMENTS`.\n291: \n292: Route by:\n293: \n294: - Empty arguments.\n295: - First-word action keywords, case-insensitive.\n296: - Natural-language query patterns.\n297: - Single ambiguous words.\n298: - Flags and options.\n299: \n300: Then define one handler section per action. Show example routing in a table so future maintainers can verify behavior quickly.\n301: \n302: ### Step 10: Implement Mode Routing When Needed\n303: \n304: For commands supporting `:auto` and `:confirm`, document mode detection:\n305: \n306: | Pattern | Mode | Behavior |\n307: | --- | --- | --- |\n308: | `/command:auto` | Autonomous | Execute without user approval gates |\n309: | `/command:confirm` | Interactive | Pause at each step for user approval |\n310: | `/command` | Prompt | Ask user to choose execution mode |\n311: \n312: Autonomous mode self-validates at checkpoints, makes informed decisions, and records significant decisions.\n313: \n314: Interactive mode pauses after each step for approval, presents options such as approve, review details, modify, skip, or abort, and records user decisions.\n315: \n316: If the mode-based command is large or has visible dashboards/prompts/results, use the router/presentation split.\n317: \n318: ### Step 11: Author The Router As A First-Class Command Type\n319: \n320: A router is a first-class command type, not a loose refactor. Its `.md` is a thin dispatcher: verify the orchestrating agent, resolve mode and arguments, then hand off to owned assets (a presentation `.txt`, optional `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`, or scripts). It carries no inline dashboards, prompts, or result templates.\n321: \n322: **Detection signature.** The validator treats a command as a router when any of:\n323: \n324: - a `render-command-contract` marker is present (the compiled-stub variant, which has no authored section requirements); or\n325: - a `Presentation Boundary` section is present; or\n326: - two or more of `{Router Contract, Owned Assets, Mode Routing, Execution Targets}` co-occur.\n327: \n328: **Minimal core vs recommended.** A router must include the blocking core only: `Owned Assets` and `Presentation Boundary`. The remaining canonical sections — `Router Contract`, `Mode Routing`, `Execution Targets`, `Workflow Summary` — are recommended and surface as non-blocking warnings when absent. Author the full shape for new routers; the minimal core lets incremental migrations land without failing.\n329: \n330: **Canonical vocabulary (numbered `## N.`, full integers).** Use exactly these H2 names, in this order, for a fully-shaped router:\n331: \n332: ```text\n333: ## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT\n334: ## 2. OWNED ASSETS\n335: ## 3. MODE ROUTING\n336: ## 4. EXECUTION TARGETS\n337: ## 5. PRESENTATION BOUNDARY\n338: ## 6. WORKFLOW SUMMARY\n339: ```\n340: \n341: Do not invent divergent synonyms (`Routing Assets`, `Workflow Routing`, `Execution Order`); the validator alias-normalizes those as a safety net, but the authored end state is the canonical names above.\n342: \n343: **Ownership boundary.** The router owns: the mandatory input gate or Phase 0, the owned-assets table, mode resolution, argument routing, execution-target selection, the presentation boundary, and a short workflow summary. The presentation asset owns: startup prompts and consolidated setup questions, auto fail-fast display text, dashboard and checkpoint layouts, success and failure result templates, and next-step suggestions. The router must not contain inline startup-question wording, dashboard templates, result templates, or next-step wording when a presentation asset exists. The split is behavior-preserving: move display content, do not change routing semantics.\n344: \n345: **Variants (one type, differing only by hand-off — not by required sections):**\n346: \n347: - Workflow-YAML-backed — routes execution into `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml` workflow assets (for example the deep-large and speckit families).\n348: - Direct-dispatch-script — dispatches directly to tools or scripts, no workflow YAML (for example the skill-benchmark, doctor, and memory families).\n349: - Compiled-stub — a generated stub carrying the `render-command-contract` marker whose contract is rendered at invocation; exempt from authored section requirements (retained variant; no command currently uses it — the deep commands are full authored routers).\n350: \n351: Use `assets/command_router_template.md` for the canonical numbered router skeleton, and `assets/command_presentation_template.md` for the full presentation asset skeleton.\n352: \n353: ### Step 12: Add Destructive-Action Safety\n354: \n355: For commands that delete data or make irreversible changes, include:\n356: \n357: - Frontmatter that makes destructive intent visible when appropriate.\n358: - Confirmation by default.\n359: - `--confirm` only when explicitly designed to skip the prompt.\n360: - Affected-state display before execution.\n361: - Clear list of items that will be deleted or changed.\n362: - Execution logging.\n363: - Completion verification.\n364: - Recovery or rebuild guidance.\n365: - `STATUS=CANCELLED ACTION=cancelled` when the user aborts.\n366: \n367: Do not ship destructive commands without confirmation and recovery design.\n368: \n369: ### Step 13: Validate Before Delivery\n370: \n371: Before publishing or claiming the command is valid, verify:\n372: \n373: - `description` exists, is action-oriented, and is single-line.\n374: - `argument-hint` exists when arguments are expected.\n375: - `allowed-tools` lists only tools actually used.\n376: - Required `<arguments>` have a mandatory gate immediately after frontmatter.\n377: - The gate forbids inference and waits for explicit input.\n378: - Section numbering uses full integers only.\n379: - H2 headers follow `## N. SECTION-NAME`.\n380: - Instructions are actionable.\n381: - Examples cover two or three likely invocations.\n382: - Status output uses a structured pattern.\n383: - Thin routers contain no presentation templates when a presentation asset exists.\n384: - Router commands carry the blocking core (`OWNED ASSETS` + `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`) and use the canonical numbered vocabulary from Step 11; remaining router sections are present or intentionally left as warnings.\n385: \n386: Run shared validators when available:\n387: \n388: ```bash\n389: python3 ../shared/scripts/validate_document.py <command-file.md> --type command\n390: python3 ../shared/scripts/extract_structure.py <command-file.md>\n391: ```\n392: \n393: Exit code `0` from `validate_document.py` is required before stating that the command document is structurally valid. If validation cannot be run, say that explicitly.\n394: \n395: ---\n396: \n397: ## 4. RULES\n398: \n399: Always:\n400: \n401: 1. Read existing target files before editing.\n402: 2. Use the smallest command type that fits the workflow.\n403: 3. Put executable workflow steps in the command, not only in references.\n404: 4. Use `argument-hint` for expected user input.\n405: 5. Add a mandatory gate for required arguments.\n406: 6. Keep `description` concise, single-line, and invocation-oriented.\n407: 7. Keep `allowed-tools` least-privilege and accurate.\n408: 8. Use fully qualified MCP tool IDs in `allowed-tools`.\n409: 9. Keep presentation text in the presentation asset when using a split.\n410: 10. Validate with shared create-quality-control scripts before delivery.\n411: 11. Keep this nested packet free of `graph-metadata.json`.\n412: \n413: Never:\n414: \n415: 1. Never create a command for one-off work that does not need reuse.\n416: 2. Never skip mandatory gates for required arguments.\n417: 3. Never infer missing required input from context or conversation history.\n418: 4. Never use broad `allowed-tools` just in case.\n419: 5. Never put dashboards, startup prompts, or result templates inside a thin router when a presentation asset exists.\n420: 6. Never omit confirmation gates for destructive or irreversible actions.\n421: 7. Never turn a command into long reference documentation.\n422: 8. Never add advisor identity metadata inside this nested packet.\n423: 9. Never claim structural validity without running validation or stating it was not run.\n424: \n425: Escalate if:\n426: \n427: 1. The command name, namespace, or invocation contract is unclear.\n428: 2. Required arguments cannot be safely defaulted.\n429: 3. The command would perform destructive work without explicit confirmation requirements.\n430: 4. Tool permissions are broader than the workflow appears to need.\n431: 5. Router logic and presentation wording cannot be separated without changing behavior.\n432: 6. The request belongs to a skill, agent, or one-off task instead of a slash command.\n433: \n434: ---\n435: \n436: ## 5. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n437: \n438: A command produced through this packet is complete when:\n439: \n440: - The correct component type was chosen: the workflow genuinely warrants a slash command rather than a skill, agent, or one-off task.\n441: - Frontmatter is well-formed: a single-line, action-oriented `description`, an `argument-hint` whenever user input is expected, and a least-privilege `allowed-tools` list using fully qualified MCP tool IDs.\n442: - Every required `<argument>` has a mandatory input gate immediately after frontmatter that forbids inference and waits for explicit input.\n443: - The body is executable and instruction-oriented, with full-integer `## N. SECTION-NAME` headings, actionable steps, two or three example invocations, and structured status output.\n444: - Router commands keep the blocking core (`OWNED ASSETS` plus `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`), use the canonical numbered vocabulary, and hold no presentation templates when a presentation asset exists.\n445: - Shared validation was run: `validate_document.py` exits `0`, or its absence is stated explicitly rather than assumed.\n446: \n447: ---\n448: \n449: ## 6. DEEP DETAIL REFERENCES\n450: \n451: Use these only for overflow detail, long examples, and exact skeletons:\n452: \n453: - `references/README.md` - overflow route map for this packet; indexes the single-concern reference files below.\n454: - `references/worked_example.md` - the canonical file contract plus a fully worked split command (router `.md` and presentation `.txt`).\n455: - `references/router_presentation_split.md` - router/presentation ownership, the before/after split transformation, and the behavior-preserving rule.\n456: - `references/argument_hints_and_modes.md` - argument-hint design patterns, `:auto`/`:confirm` mode design, and frontmatter/description budget tips.\n457: - `references/common_pitfalls.md` - command-vs-skill-vs-agent selection and the common command-authoring mistakes table.\n458: - `assets/command_template.md` - exhaustive command type templates, examples, vocabulary, and validation checklist.\n459: - `assets/command_router_template.md` - canonical numbered router skeleton with variant call-outs.\n460: - `assets/command_presentation_template.md` - full `_presentation.txt` skeleton for split command families.\n461: - `../shared/references/core_standards.md` - shared document quality standards.\n462: - `../shared/references/validation.md` - shared validation expectations.\n463: - `../shared/scripts/validate_document.py` - blocking structure validation.\n464: - `../shared/scripts/extract_structure.py` - structure extraction for review.\n\n(End of file - total 464 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: create-command\ndescription: Scaffold OpenCode slash commands with explicit argument hints, allowed tools, and router/presentation separation.\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\nversion: 1.0.1.1\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: create-command, slash command, opencode command, argument-hint, allowed-tools, command router, presentation contract, thin router, command scaffold -->\n\n# Create Command\n\n`create-command` is the command-authoring workflow packet of the `sk-doc` parent hub. It creates and improves OpenCode slash commands under `.opencode/commands/` with executable workflows, precise frontmatter, required input gates, least-privilege tools, and router/presentation separation when needed.\n\nThis SKILL.md contains the core creation workflow. Use the `references/` route map (`references/README.md`), `assets/command_template.md`, `assets/command_router_template.md`, `assets/command_presentation_template.md`, and `../shared/` only for exhaustive examples, edge cases, and validator implementation detail.\n\nThis packet is lean and self-contained. The advisor identity lives at the `sk-doc` hub root; do not add packet-local `graph-metadata.json`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: create-command\ndescription: Scaffold OpenCode slash commands with explicit argument hints, allowed tools, and router/presentation separation.\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\nversion: 1.0.1.1\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: create-command, slash command, opencode command, argument-hint, allowed-tools, command router, presentation contract, thin router, command scaffold -->\n\n# Create Command\n\n`create-command` is the command-authoring workflow packet of the `sk-doc` parent hub. It creates and improves OpenCode slash commands under `.opencode/commands/` with executable workflows, precise frontmatter, required input gates, least-privilege tools, and router/presentation separation when needed.\n\nThis SKILL.md contains the core creation workflow. Use the `references/` route map (`references/README.md`), `assets/command_template.md`, `assets/command_router_template.md`, `assets/command_presentation_template.md`, and `../shared/` only for exhaustive examples, edge cases, and validator implementation detail.\n\nThis packet is lean and self-contained. The advisor identity lives at the `sk-doc` hub root; do not add packet-local `graph-metadata.json`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\n### Activation Triggers\n\nUse this packet when the request involves:\n\n- Creating a new OpenCode slash command.\n- Refactoring a command into a thin router plus owned presentation asset.\n- Adding or fixing command frontmatter, especially `argument-hint` and `allowed-tools`.\n- Designing command argument handling with `$ARGUMENTS`.\n- Authoring a namespace command such as `/namespace:action`.\n- Separating visible prompts, dashboards, result templates, or next-step wording into a presentation contract.\n- Checking whether a workflow should be a command instead of a skill, agent, or one-off task.\n\nKeyword triggers: `create command`, `/create:command`, `slash command`, `OpenCode command`, `argument-hint`, `allowed-tools`, `command template`, `router presentation split`, `thin router`, `presentation contract`, `$ARGUMENTS`.\n\n### When NOT to Use\n\nUse another `sk-doc` packet when:\n\n- The request is to create a skill or parent hub. Use `create-skill`.\n- The request is to create an agent. Use `create-agent`.\n- The task is a README, install guide, feature catalog, manual testing playbook, benchmark package, flowchart, or changelog. Use `create-readme`, `create-feature-catalog`, `create-manual-testing-playbook`, `create-benchmark`, `create-flowchart`, or `create-changelog`.\n- The task audits, validates, scores, or optimizes an existing command document. Use `create-quality-control`.\n- The task is one-time work that does not need a reusable slash command.\n- The command already exists and the user only wants runtime debugging.\n- The requested workflow is destructive or externally privileged but lacks confirmation and rollback requirements.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SMART ROUTING\n\nThese triggers route a request into this command-authoring packet. Execution-mode suffixes are command syntax, not packet-selection triggers. When the surface is a slash command, stay in this packet and continue to the creation workflow below.\n\n### Router Resilience\n\nThis packet routes by command-authoring intent and the requested component surface. It does not use runtime keyed resource discovery through `references/<key>/` because its references are flat.\n\n- Load optional markdown resources only after resolving them under this packet and confirming they exist.\n- Treat `references/README.md` as the fallback route map when command intent or component surface is unclear.\n- Ask for the missing command purpose, invocation shape, or component type instead of silently loading no resources.\n- Do not add a full `references/<key>/` or `assets/<key>/` runtime-key router unless this packet gains real keyed resource subdirectories.\n\n### Resource Loading Sequence\n\nThe packet keeps its existing flat-resource routing while using the shared resilience call sequence:\n\n```python\ndef discover_markdown_resources():\n    return flat markdown resources under this packet's `references/` and `assets/` folders\n\ndef _guard_in_skill(relative_path):\n    # Keep packet-local markdown paths in scope; retain explicitly documented shared routes.\n    confirm the path is an allowed markdown resource for this packet\n\ndef load_if_available(relative_path, inventory, seen):\n    guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n    if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n        load(guarded)\n        seen.add(guarded)\n\ndef route_create_command_request(request):\n    inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n    intents = score_intents(request)  # command-authoring intent and component surface\n    selected = select_intents(intents)\n    routing_key = get_routing_key(request, selected)\n    if not selected or the command purpose or component surface is unclear:\n        load_if_available(\"references/README.md\", inventory, seen)\n        return UNKNOWN_FALLBACK\n    return route by the existing command-authoring intent and component-surface rules\n```\n\n`UNKNOWN_FALLBACK` asks for the command purpose, invocation shape, or component type. The sequence discovers the current flat resources at routing time, guards and loads only available resources without duplicates, then applies the activation triggers and command-type rules already defined below.\n\n---\n\n## 3. HOW IT WORKS: CREATION WORKFLOW\n\nFollow these steps in order.\n\n### Step 1: Decide Whether A Command Is Correct\n\nCreate a command only when the workflow is repeatable and has defined steps.\n\nUse a command when the workflow:\n\n- Automates a multi-step process.\n- Needs repeatable execution across sessions.\n- Needs `$ARGUMENTS` parsing or mode routing.\n- Needs user-controlled execution pace such as `:auto` or `:confirm`.\n- Needs confirmation gates for destructive or privileged actions.\n- Benefits from explicit tool restrictions.\n\nUse a skill instead when the content is reusable reference knowledge, domain guidance, standards, or patterns shared by multiple workflows. Do not create a command for one-off work.\n\n### Step 2: Resolve Invocation And Path\n\nDetermine the command invocation before writing:\n\n- Root command: `.opencode/commands/<command>.md` becomes `/<command>`.\n- Namespace command: `.opencode/commands/<namespace>/<action>.md` becomes `/<namespace>:<action>`.\n- Namespace and action names use lowercase hyphen-case.\n\nFor grouped related actions, prefer a namespace directory:\n\n```text\n.opencode/commands/\n└── <namespace>/\n    ├── <action1>.md\n    ├── <action2>.md\n    └── <action3>.md\n```\n\n### Step 3: Read Existing Files First\n\nBefore editing an existing command or owned asset, read it completely enough to understand current behavior. Preserve behavior unless the user explicitly asks to change it.\n\nFor new commands, inspect nearby commands in the same namespace when available so structure and vocabulary match the command family.\n\n### Step 4: Classify The Command Type\n\nChoose the smallest command type that fits:\n\n| Type | Use When | Typical Shape |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Simple | Single action, few arguments | One `.md` file, direct steps |\n| Workflow | Multi-step process with checkpoints | One `.md` file with overview, instructions, recovery |\n| Mode-based | Supports `:auto` / `:confirm` | Thin router plus owned assets when complex |\n| Router | Thin dispatcher: verify agent, resolve mode/args, hand off to owned assets | Router `.md` plus owned presentation `.txt` and optional workflow YAML or scripts |\n| Argument dispatch | Multiple action keywords or query forms | ASCII routing tree plus handlers |\n| Destructive | Deletes data or irreversible changes | Explicit confirmation, affected-state display, recovery guidance |\n| Namespace | Related commands grouped together | Directory under `.opencode/commands/` |\n\nIf the command combines patterns, parse mode first, then dispatch remaining arguments.\n\n### Step 5: Choose The Output Package Shape\n\nFor a simple or medium command, create or update:\n\n```text\n.opencode/commands/<command>.md\n```\n\nFor a namespace command, create or update:\n\n```text\n.opencode/commands/<namespace>/<action>.md\n```\n\nFor a split mode-based workflow command, create or update:\n\n```text\n.opencode/commands/<namespace>/<action>.md\n.opencode/commands/<namespace>/assets/<namespace>_<action>_presentation.txt\n.opencode/commands/<namespace>/assets/<namespace>_<action>_auto.yaml\n.opencode/commands/<namespace>/assets/<namespace>_<action>_confirm.yaml\n```\n\nUse `_auto.yaml` and `_confirm.yaml` only for workflow-backed families that route execution into workflow assets. Direct-router families dispatch directly to tools/scripts and do not need workflow YAML.\n\nFor a compiled-stub router, the `.md` is a generated thin stub carrying the `render-command-contract` marker; its section shape is rendered from a compiled source at invocation, not authored in the file. Do not hand-write section headings into a compiled stub, and keep its owned presentation/workflow assets alongside it:\n\n```text\n.opencode/commands/<namespace>/<action>.md            # compiled stub (render-command-contract marker)\n.opencode/commands/<namespace>/assets/<namespace>_<action>_presentation.txt\n```\n\n### Step 6: Author Frontmatter First\n\nEvery command starts with YAML frontmatter.\n\nRequired:\n\n```yaml\n---\ndescription: Action-oriented single-line description\n---\n```\n\nRecommended when applicable:\n\n```yaml\nargument-hint: \"<required> [optional] [--flag]\"\nallowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash\n```\n\nRules:\n\n- Keep `description` single-line, action-oriented, and concise.\n- Target descriptions at or under 110 characters.\n- Do not use YAML block scalars for `description`.\n- Use `argument-hint` whenever the command expects user input.\n- Use `<angle-brackets>` only for required arguments.\n- Use `[square-brackets]` for optional arguments.\n- List every tool the command actually uses in `allowed-tools`.\n- Do not add broad tools just in case.\n- For MCP tools in `allowed-tools`, use fully qualified names such as `mcp__<server>__<tool>`.\n- Bare tool names such as `memory_context` belong in prose only, not `allowed-tools`.\n\n### Step 7: Add Mandatory Input Gates\n\nIf `argument-hint` contains any required `<argument>`, add the mandatory gate immediately after frontmatter, before all other content.\n\nThe gate must:\n\n- Check whether `$ARGUMENTS` is empty, undefined, or whitespace-only.\n- Ignore mode suffixes when determining whether required content exists.\n- Stop immediately when required input is missing.\n- Ask a context-specific question with clear options or expected reply format.\n- Wait for the user response.\n- Use only `$ARGUMENTS` or the user's explicit answer as the input.\n- Forbid inference from context, screenshots, conversation history, or open files.\n\nFor multi-input commands, use a blocking phase pattern:\n\n- Phase 1: input collection.\n- Phase 2: prerequisite/context verification.\n- Phase status verification table.\n- Violation self-detection block.\n\nEvery workflow command with blocking phases must include violation self-detection: if a required phase was skipped, stop, state the violation, return to the phase, and complete it properly.\n\n### Step 8: Write The Command Body\n\nUse executable, instruction-oriented sections. Commands are workflows, not long reference manuals.\n\nCommon section order:\n\n1. Title and purpose.\n2. Contract.\n3. Workflow overview or argument routing.\n4. Instructions.\n5. Failure recovery and error handling when needed.\n6. Examples.\n7. Status output patterns or completion report.\n\nUse these conventions:\n\n- H1: plain command title, or a blocking semantic title for mandatory gates.\n- H2: `## N. SECTION-NAME`, using full integers only.\n- H3 steps: `### Step N: Description`.\n- Do not use decimal steps such as `1.5` or `2.5`.\n- Put sub-activities in bullets under a numbered step.\n- Use dividers between major sections when they improve scanability.\n- Return structured statuses such as `STATUS=OK`, `STATUS=FAIL ERROR=\"<message>\"`, or `STATUS=CANCELLED ACTION=cancelled`.\n\nApproved common H2 section names include:\n\n- `PURPOSE`\n- `CONTRACT`\n- `WORKFLOW OVERVIEW`\n- `INSTRUCTIONS`\n- `ARGUMENT ROUTING`\n- `REFERENCE`\n- `EXAMPLES`\n- `RELATED COMMANDS`\n- `TOOL SIGNATURES`\n- `USER INPUT`\n\nApproved canonical H2 section names for router commands (see Step 11):\n\n- `ROUTER CONTRACT`\n- `OWNED ASSETS`\n- `MODE ROUTING`\n- `EXECUTION TARGETS`\n- `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`\n- `WORKFLOW SUMMARY`\n\n### Step 9: Implement Argument Dispatch When Needed\n\nFor commands with multiple entry points, include an ASCII routing tree based on `$ARGUMENTS`.\n\nRoute by:\n\n- Empty arguments.\n- First-word action keywords, case-insensitive.\n- Natural-language query patterns.\n- Single ambiguous words.\n- Flags and options.\n\nThen define one handler section per action. Show example routing in a table so future maintainers can verify behavior quickly.\n\n### Step 10: Implement Mode Routing When Needed\n\nFor commands supporting `:auto` and `:confirm`, document mode detection:\n\n| Pattern | Mode | Behavior |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| `/command:auto` | Autonomous | Execute without user approval gates |\n| `/command:confirm` | Interactive | Pause at each step for user approval |\n| `/command` | Prompt | Ask user to choose execution mode |\n\nAutonomous mode self-validates at checkpoints, makes informed decisions, and records significant decisions.\n\nInteractive mode pauses after each step for approval, presents options such as approve, review details, modify, skip, or abort, and records user decisions.\n\nIf the mode-based command is large or has visible dashboards/prompts/results, use the router/presentation split.\n\n### Step 11: Author The Router As A First-Class Command Type\n\nA router is a first-class command type, not a loose refactor. Its `.md` is a thin dispatcher: verify the orchestrating agent, resolve mode and arguments, then hand off to owned assets (a presentation `.txt`, optional `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`, or scripts). It carries no inline dashboards, prompts, or result templates.\n\n**Detection signature.** The validator treats a command as a router when any of:\n\n- a `render-command-contract` marker is present (the compiled-stub variant, which has no authored section requirements); or\n- a `Presentation Boundary` section is present; or\n- two or more of `{Router Contract, Owned Assets, Mode Routing, Execution Targets}` co-occur.\n\n**Minimal core vs recommended.** A router must include the blocking core only: `Owned Assets` and `Presentation Boundary`. The remaining canonical sections — `Router Contract`, `Mode Routing`, `Execution Targets`, `Workflow Summary` — are recommended and surface as non-blocking warnings when absent. Author the full shape for new routers; the minimal core lets incremental migrations land without failing.\n\n**Canonical vocabulary (numbered `## N.`, full integers).** Use exactly these H2 names, in this order, for a fully-shaped router:\n\n```text\n## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT\n## 2. OWNED ASSETS\n## 3. MODE ROUTING\n## 4. EXECUTION TARGETS\n## 5. PRESENTATION BOUNDARY\n## 6. WORKFLOW SUMMARY\n```\n\nDo not invent divergent synonyms (`Routing Assets`, `Workflow Routing`, `Execution Order`); the validator alias-normalizes those as a safety net, but the authored end state is the canonical names above.\n\n**Ownership boundary.** The router owns: the mandatory input gate or Phase 0, the owned-assets table, mode resolution, argument routing, execution-target selection, the presentation boundary, and a short workflow summary. The presentation asset owns: startup prompts and consolidated setup questions, auto fail-fast display text, dashboard and checkpoint layouts, success and failure result templates, and next-step suggestions. The router must not contain inline startup-question wording, dashboard templates, result templates, or next-step wording when a presentation asset exists. The split is behavior-preserving: move display content, do not change routing semantics.\n\n**Variants (one type, differing only by hand-off — not by required sections):**\n\n- Workflow-YAML-backed — routes execution into `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml` workflow assets (for example the deep-large and speckit families).\n- Direct-dispatch-script — dispatches directly to tools or scripts, no workflow YAML (for example the skill-benchmark, doctor, and memory families).\n- Compiled-stub — a generated stub carrying the `render-command-contract` marker whose contract is rendered at invocation; exempt from authored section requirements (retained variant; no command currently uses it — the deep commands are full authored routers).\n\nUse `assets/command_router_template.md` for the canonical numbered router skeleton, and `assets/command_presentation_template.md` for the full presentation asset skeleton.\n\n### Step 12: Add Destructive-Action Safety\n\nFor commands that delete data or make irreversible changes, include:\n\n- Frontmatter that makes destructive intent visible when appropriate.\n- Confirmation by default.\n- `--confirm` only when explicitly designed to skip the prompt.\n- Affected-state display before execution.\n- Clear list of items that will be deleted or changed.\n- Execution logging.\n- Completion verification.\n- Recovery or rebuild guidance.\n- `STATUS=CANCELLED ACTION=cancelled` when the user aborts.\n\nDo not ship destructive commands without confirmation and recovery design.\n\n### Step 13: Validate Before Delivery\n\nBefore publishing or claiming the command is valid, verify:\n\n- `description` exists, is action-oriented, and is single-line.\n- `argument-hint` exists when arguments are expected.\n- `allowed-tools` lists only tools actually used.\n- Required `<arguments>` have a mandatory gate immediately after frontmatter.\n- The gate forbids inference and waits for explicit input.\n- Section numbering uses full integers only.\n- H2 headers follow `## N. SECTION-NAME`.\n- Instructions are actionable.\n- Examples cover two or three likely invocations.\n- Status output uses a structured pattern.\n- Thin routers contain no presentation templates when a presentation asset exists.\n- Router commands carry the blocking core (`OWNED ASSETS` + `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`) and use the canonical numbered vocabulary from Step 11; remaining router sections are present or intentionally left as warnings.\n\nRun shared validators when available:\n\n```bash\npython3 ../shared/scripts/validate_document.py <command-file.md> --type command\npython3 ../shared/scripts/extract_structure.py <command-file.md>\n```\n\nExit code `0` from `validate_document.py` is required before stating that the command document is structurally valid. If validation cannot be run, say that explicitly.\n\n---\n\n## 4. RULES\n\nAlways:\n\n1. Read existing target files before editing.\n2. Use the smallest command type that fits the workflow.\n3. Put executable workflow steps in the command, not only in references.\n4. Use `argument-hint` for expected user input.\n5. Add a mandatory gate for required arguments.\n6. Keep `description` concise, single-line, and invocation-oriented.\n7. Keep `allowed-tools` least-privilege and accurate.\n8. Use fully qualified MCP tool IDs in `allowed-tools`.\n9. Keep presentation text in the presentation asset when using a split.\n10. Validate with shared create-quality-control scripts before delivery.\n11. Keep this nested packet free of `graph-metadata.json`.\n\nNever:\n\n1. Never create a command for one-off work that does not need reuse.\n2. Never skip mandatory gates for required arguments.\n3. Never infer missing required input from context or conversation history.\n4. Never use broad `allowed-tools` just in case.\n5. Never put dashboards, startup prompts, or result templates inside a thin router when a presentation asset exists.\n6. Never omit confirmation gates for destructive or irreversible actions.\n7. Never turn a command into long reference documentation.\n8. Never add advisor identity metadata inside this nested packet.\n9. Never claim structural validity without running validation or stating it was not run.\n\nEscalate if:\n\n1. The command name, namespace, or invocation contract is unclear.\n2. Required arguments cannot be safely defaulted.\n3. The command would perform destructive work without explicit confirmation requirements.\n4. Tool permissions are broader than the workflow appears to need.\n5. Router logic and presentation wording cannot be separated without changing behavior.\n6. The request belongs to a skill, agent, or one-off task instead of a slash command.\n\n---\n\n## 5. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n\nA command produced through this packet is complete when:\n\n- The correct component type was chosen: the workflow genuinely warrants a slash command rather than a skill, agent, or one-off task.\n- Frontmatter is well-formed: a single-line, action-oriented `description`, an `argument-hint` whenever user input is expected, and a least-privilege `allowed-tools` list using fully qualified MCP tool IDs.\n- Every required `<argument>` has a mandatory input gate immediately after frontmatter that forbids inference and waits for explicit input.\n- The body is executable and instruction-oriented, with full-integer `## N. SECTION-NAME` headings, actionable steps, two or three example invocations, and structured status output.\n- Router commands keep the blocking core (`OWNED ASSETS` plus `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`), use the canonical numbered vocabulary, and hold no presentation templates when a presentation asset exists.\n- Shared validation was run: `validate_document.py` exits `0`, or its absence is stated explicitly rather than assumed.\n\n---\n\n## 6. DEEP DETAIL REFERENCES\n\nUse these only for overflow detail, long examples, and exact skeletons:\n\n- `references/README.md` - overflow route map for this packet; indexes the single-concern reference files below.\n- `references/worked_example.md` - the canonical file contract plus a fully worked split command (router `.md` and presentation `.txt`).\n- `references/router_presentation_split.md` - router/presentation ownership, the before/after split transformation, and the behavior-preserving rule.\n- `references/argument_hints_and_modes.md` - argument-hint design patterns, `:auto`/`:confirm` mode design, and frontmatter/description budget tips.\n- `references/common_pitfalls.md` - command-vs-skill-vs-agent selection and the common command-authoring mistakes table.\n- `assets/command_template.md` - exhaustive command type templates, examples, vocabulary, and validation checklist.\n- `assets/command_router_template.md` - canonical numbered router skeleton with variant call-outs.\n- `assets/command_presentation_template.md` - full `_presentation.txt` skeleton for split command families.\n- `../shared/references/core_standards.md` - shared document quality standards.\n- `../shared/references/validation.md` - shared validation expectations.\n- `../shared/scripts/validate_document.py` - blocking structure validation.\n- `../shared/scripts/extract_structure.py` - structure extraction for review.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":464,"totalLines":464,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1784180560345,"end":1784180560352}},"id":"prt_f6972d1d8001TPscmr3CS0WiC3","sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","messageID":"msg_f6972a67d001NDlWgKNP9yChdH"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1784180561309,"sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","part":{"id":"prt_f6972d59b001ATVoOF1Hj77Tu4","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","messageID":"msg_f6972a67d001NDlWgKNP9yChdH","sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":76495,"input":1277,"output":111,"reasoning":35,"cache":{"write":0,"read":75072}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1784180574364,"sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","part":{"id":"prt_f69730896001CBUuuEopulgSnN","messageID":"msg_f6972d97f001vFSaaIbVo79G3z","sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1784180579830,"sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","part":{"id":"prt_f69731096001c2VQEZmQinEFJ4","messageID":"msg_f6972d97f001vFSaaIbVo79G3z","sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","type":"text","text":"Let me read the command templates, the validator, and the 066 scorecard/remediation outputs.","time":{"start":1784180576406,"end":1784180579825}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784180579840,"sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_7719a9d213074397b12cfe05","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_router_template.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_router_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Command Router Template\n3: description: Canonical skeleton for thin router commands with owned assets and presentation boundaries.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"command router template\"\n6:   - \"thin router command\"\n7:   - \"router presentation split\"\n8:   - \"router command skeleton\"\n9:   - \"owned assets presentation boundary\"\n10: importance_tier: normal\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 1.0.0.0\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Command Router Template\n16: \n17: Canonical skeleton for a first-class **router** command: a thin dispatcher whose `.md`\n18: verifies the orchestrating agent, resolves mode and arguments, then hands off to owned\n19: assets (a presentation `.txt`, optional `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`, or scripts). The\n20: router carries no inline dashboards, prompts, or result templates.\n21: \n22: ---\n23: \n24: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n25: \n26: Copy the skeleton below and fill the placeholders. Use it whenever `create-command`\n27: Step 11 classifies the command as a router.\n28: \n29: - **Blocking core (required):** `OWNED ASSETS` and `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`.\n30: - **Recommended (non-blocking warnings when absent):** `ROUTER CONTRACT`, `MODE ROUTING`,\n31:   `EXECUTION TARGETS`, `WORKFLOW SUMMARY`.\n32: - **Numbering:** H2 headers use `## N.` with full integers only, in the canonical order.\n33: - **Vocabulary is fixed.** Do not substitute synonyms such as `Routing Assets`,\n34:   `Workflow Routing`, or `Execution Order`; the validator alias-normalizes those as a\n35:   safety net, but the authored end state is the canonical names below.\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 2. CANONICAL SKELETON\n40: \n41: ```markdown\n42: ---\n43: description: <action-oriented single-line description, modes noted>\n44: argument-hint: \"<required> [:auto|:confirm] [optional] [--flag]\"\n45: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob\n46: ---\n47: \n48: # <Command Title>\n49: \n50: Thin router for <workflow>. This command verifies the orchestrating agent, resolves the\n51: execution mode, loads the presentation contract, then executes the owned assets.\n52: \n53: ## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT\n54: \n55: Do not dispatch agents or write artifacts from this Markdown file; that behavior is owned\n56: by the workflow/script assets. Load the presentation contract before showing any startup\n57: question, checkpoint, dashboard, success output, failure output, or next-step prompt.\n58: \n59: ---\n60: \n61: ## 2. OWNED ASSETS\n62: \n63: | Purpose | Asset |\n64: |---------|-------|\n65: | Presentation source of truth | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_presentation.txt` |\n66: | Auto workflow (workflow-YAML variant only) | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_auto.yaml` |\n67: | Confirm workflow (workflow-YAML variant only) | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_confirm.yaml` |\n68: \n69: ---\n70: \n71: ## 3. MODE ROUTING\n72: \n73: 1. Parse `$ARGUMENTS` for `:auto` / `:confirm` (and any command-specific mode suffixes).\n74: 2. Treat remaining flags as workflow inputs, not execution modes.\n75: 3. If no mode suffix is present, use the presentation contract's startup prompt to ask.\n76: 4. Load the selected execution target and run it step by step.\n77: \n78: ---\n79: \n80: ## 4. EXECUTION TARGETS\n81: \n82: | Mode | Target |\n83: |------|--------|\n84: | `:auto` | `<auto workflow YAML, or the script/tool the router dispatches>` |\n85: | `:confirm` or interactive choice | `<confirm workflow YAML, or the interactive path>` |\n86: \n87: ---\n88: \n89: ## 5. PRESENTATION BOUNDARY\n90: \n91: The following content lives only in the presentation asset, never inline in this router:\n92: \n93: - Startup-question wording and reply format.\n94: - Checkpoint and dashboard display templates.\n95: - Success and failure result templates.\n96: - Next-step suggestions and final user prompt wording.\n97: \n98: ---\n99: \n100: ## 6. WORKFLOW SUMMARY\n101: \n102: A short, numbered recap of the end-to-end flow the router orchestrates, pointing at the\n103: owned assets rather than restating their content.\n104: ```\n105: \n106: ---\n107: \n108: ## 3. VARIANTS\n109: \n110: One router type; the variants differ only by hand-off, never by required sections.\n111: \n112: | Variant | Hand-off | Example families | Notes |\n113: |---------|----------|------------------|-------|\n114: | Workflow-YAML-backed | Router routes modes into `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml` | speckit, create, deep-large | Keep `EXECUTION TARGETS` pointing at the YAML assets. |\n115: | Direct-dispatch-script | Router dispatches straight to tools or scripts | memory, doctor, skill-benchmark | No workflow YAML; recommended sections may stay as warnings. |\n116: | Compiled-stub | Contract rendered at invocation from a compiled source | — (retained; none active) | Carries a `render-command-contract` marker; exempt from authored section requirements — do not hand-write section headings. |\n117: \n118: ---\n119: \n120: ## 4. RELATED RESOURCES\n121: \n122: - `command_template.md` - exhaustive command type templates and vocabulary.\n123: - `command_presentation_template.md` - full `_presentation.txt` skeleton for the owned presentation asset.\n124: - `../SKILL.md` Step 11 - the first-class router authoring workflow.\n\n(End of file - total 124 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Command Router Template\ndescription: Canonical skeleton for thin router commands with owned assets and presentation boundaries.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"command router template\"\n  - \"thin router command\"\n  - \"router presentation split\"\n  - \"router command skeleton\"\n  - \"owned assets presentation boundary\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Command Router Template\n\nCanonical skeleton for a first-class **router** command: a thin dispatcher whose `.md`\nverifies the orchestrating agent, resolves mode and arguments, then hands off to owned\nassets (a presentation `.txt`, optional `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`, or scripts). The\nrouter carries no inline dashboards, prompts, or result templates.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_router_template.md","text":"---\ntitle: Command Router Template\ndescription: Canonical skeleton for thin router commands with owned assets and presentation boundaries.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"command router template\"\n  - \"thin router command\"\n  - \"router presentation split\"\n  - \"router command skeleton\"\n  - \"owned assets presentation boundary\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Command Router Template\n\nCanonical skeleton for a first-class **router** command: a thin dispatcher whose `.md`\nverifies the orchestrating agent, resolves mode and arguments, then hands off to owned\nassets (a presentation `.txt`, optional `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`, or scripts). The\nrouter carries no inline dashboards, prompts, or result templates.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nCopy the skeleton below and fill the placeholders. Use it whenever `create-command`\nStep 11 classifies the command as a router.\n\n- **Blocking core (required):** `OWNED ASSETS` and `PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`.\n- **Recommended (non-blocking warnings when absent):** `ROUTER CONTRACT`, `MODE ROUTING`,\n  `EXECUTION TARGETS`, `WORKFLOW SUMMARY`.\n- **Numbering:** H2 headers use `## N.` with full integers only, in the canonical order.\n- **Vocabulary is fixed.** Do not substitute synonyms such as `Routing Assets`,\n  `Workflow Routing`, or `Execution Order`; the validator alias-normalizes those as a\n  safety net, but the authored end state is the canonical names below.\n\n---\n\n## 2. CANONICAL SKELETON\n\n```markdown\n---\ndescription: <action-oriented single-line description, modes noted>\nargument-hint: \"<required> [:auto|:confirm] [optional] [--flag]\"\nallowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob\n---\n\n# <Command Title>\n\nThin router for <workflow>. This command verifies the orchestrating agent, resolves the\nexecution mode, loads the presentation contract, then executes the owned assets.\n\n## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT\n\nDo not dispatch agents or write artifacts from this Markdown file; that behavior is owned\nby the workflow/script assets. Load the presentation contract before showing any startup\nquestion, checkpoint, dashboard, success output, failure output, or next-step prompt.\n\n---\n\n## 2. OWNED ASSETS\n\n| Purpose | Asset |\n|---------|-------|\n| Presentation source of truth | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_presentation.txt` |\n| Auto workflow (workflow-YAML variant only) | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_auto.yaml` |\n| Confirm workflow (workflow-YAML variant only) | `.opencode/commands/<ns>/assets/<ns>_<action>_confirm.yaml` |\n\n---\n\n## 3. MODE ROUTING\n\n1. Parse `$ARGUMENTS` for `:auto` / `:confirm` (and any command-specific mode suffixes).\n2. Treat remaining flags as workflow inputs, not execution modes.\n3. If no mode suffix is present, use the presentation contract's startup prompt to ask.\n4. Load the selected execution target and run it step by step.\n\n---\n\n## 4. EXECUTION TARGETS\n\n| Mode | Target |\n|------|--------|\n| `:auto` | `<auto workflow YAML, or the script/tool the router dispatches>` |\n| `:confirm` or interactive choice | `<confirm workflow YAML, or the interactive path>` |\n\n---\n\n## 5. PRESENTATION BOUNDARY\n\nThe following content lives only in the presentation asset, never inline in this router:\n\n- Startup-question wording and reply format.\n- Checkpoint and dashboard display templates.\n- Success and failure result templates.\n- Next-step suggestions and final user prompt wording.\n\n---\n\n## 6. WORKFLOW SUMMARY\n\nA short, numbered recap of the end-to-end flow the router orchestrates, pointing at the\nowned assets rather than restating their content.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. VARIANTS\n\nOne router type; the variants differ only by hand-off, never by required sections.\n\n| Variant | Hand-off | Example families | Notes |\n|---------|----------|------------------|-------|\n| Workflow-YAML-backed | Router routes modes into `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml` | speckit, create, deep-large | Keep `EXECUTION TARGETS` pointing at the YAML assets. |\n| Direct-dispatch-script | Router dispatches straight to tools or scripts | memory, doctor, skill-benchmark | No workflow YAML; recommended sections may stay as warnings. |\n| Compiled-stub | Contract rendered at invocation from a compiled source | — (retained; none active) | Carries a `render-command-contract` marker; exempt from authored section requirements — do not hand-write section headings. |\n\n---\n\n## 4. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- `command_template.md` - exhaustive command type templates and vocabulary.\n- `command_presentation_template.md` - full `_presentation.txt` skeleton for the owned presentation asset.\n- `../SKILL.md` Step 11 - the first-class router authoring workflow.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":124,"totalLines":124,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_router_template.md","time":{"start":1784180579792,"end":1784180579836}},"id":"prt_f69731dac001MsCZoRvBw1o370","sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","messageID":"msg_f6972d97f001vFSaaIbVo79G3z"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784180579852,"sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_491d9aa213554097b0168c1c","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_template.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Command Template - OpenCode Slash Commands\n3: description: Templates and best practices for creating production-quality slash commands in OpenCode with proper frontmatter and structure.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"slash command template\"\n6:   - \"command frontmatter structure\"\n7:   - \"opencode command scaffold\"\n8:   - \"argument hint patterns\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.8.0.20\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Command Template - OpenCode Slash Commands\n15: \n16: Templates for creating slash commands with proper frontmatter, mandatory gates, and structured workflows.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### What Are OpenCode Commands?\n23: \n24: **OpenCode commands** are slash-triggered instructions (e.g., `/speckit:complete`, `/memory:save`) that automate workflows, enforce patterns, and extend AI agent capabilities. They're markdown files that define structured behavior for specific tasks.\n25: \n26: **Core Purpose**:\n27: - **Workflow automation** - Multi-step processes become single invocations\n28: - **Pattern enforcement** - Consistent behavior across sessions\n29: - **Task routing** - Arguments dispatch to appropriate handlers\n30: - **User guidance** - Structured prompts prevent errors\n31: - **Tool restriction** - Limit which tools the command can use\n32: \n33: **Key Difference from Skills**:\n34: - Commands = Actionable workflows triggered by `/command-name`\n35: - Skills = Reference documentation loaded via `Read(\".opencode/skills/<skill-name>/SKILL.md\")`\n36: \n37: ### Core Characteristics\n38: \n39: | Characteristic         | Description                                           |\n40: | ---------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |\n41: | **Markdown-based**     | Human-readable instruction files                      |\n42: | **Frontmatter-driven** | Metadata controls behavior (description, args, tools) |\n43: | **Argument-aware**     | Parse and validate user input via `$ARGUMENTS`        |\n44: | **Status-reporting**   | Return structured outcomes (`STATUS=OK\\|FAIL`)        |\n45: | **Tool-restricted**    | `allowed-tools` limits available tools                |\n46: \n47: ### How Commands Are Invoked\n48: \n49: ```\n50: User types: /command-name arguments\n51:                 │           │\n52:                 │           └─► Passed as $ARGUMENTS variable\n53:                 │\n54:                 └─► OpenCode finds .opencode/commands/command-name.md\n55:                     │\n56:                     ├─► Loads frontmatter (description, tools, hints)\n57:                     │\n58:                     ├─► Injects $ARGUMENTS into instruction body\n59:                     │\n60:                     └─► AI agent executes instructions step-by-step\n61: ```\n62: \n63: > **Description budget**: command `description:` fields share the Claude Code skill-metadata budget (default 8,000 chars total). Keep each command description **≤ 110 chars**, retain `:auto`/`:confirm` mode suffixes (advisor trigger tokens), no product enumerations. See [`assets/frontmatter_templates.md` § Description Budget & Trim Style](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for the canonical trim rules.\n64: \n65: ### Command File Location\n66: \n67: ```\n68: .opencode/\n69: └── command/\n70:     ├── simple-command.md          → /simple-command\n71:     ├── workflow-command.md        → /workflow-command\n72:     └── namespace/                  → Grouped commands\n73:         ├── action1.md             → /namespace:action1\n74:         └── action2.md             → /namespace:action2\n75: ```\n76: \n77: ### Progressive Complexity\n78: \n79: ```\n80: Level 1: Simple Command\n81:          └─ Single action, few arguments (~50-100 lines)\n82:             ↓\n83: Level 2: Workflow Command\n84:          └─ Multi-step process with validation (~100-200 lines)\n85:             ↓\n86: Level 3: Mode-Based / Dispatch Command\n87:          └─ Complex routing, user control (~150-300 lines)\n88: ```\n89: \n90: ---\n91: \n92: ## 2. WHEN TO CREATE COMMANDS\n93: \n94: ### Create Command When\n95: \n96: - Multi-step process with defined phases\n97: - Repeated task needing consistency across sessions\n98: - Requires confirmation gates (destructive actions)\n99: - Multiple argument patterns need routing\n100: - User should control execution pace (`:auto`/`:confirm` modes)\n101: - Tool restrictions needed for security/focus\n102: \n103: ### Use Skill Instead When\n104: \n105: - Content is reference material, not executable workflow\n106: - Complex domain knowledge that multiple commands might need\n107: - Reusable patterns/standards across multiple commands\n108: \n109: ### Decision Framework\n110: \n111: ```\n112: Is this a repeatable workflow with defined steps?\n113: ├─► YES\n114: │   │\n115: │   ├─► Does it need user arguments?\n116: │   │   └─► Command with argument-hint + mandatory gate\n117: │   │\n118: │   ├─► Does it have modes (auto/confirm)?\n119: │   │   └─► Mode-based command template\n120: │   │\n121: │   ├─► Is it destructive/irreversible?\n122: │   │   └─► Destructive command template\n123: │   │\n124: │   ├─► Multiple action keywords (start/stop/status)?\n125: │   │   └─► Argument dispatch pattern\n126: │   │\n127: │   └─► Simple single action?\n128: │       └─► Simple command template\n129: │\n130: └─► NO\n131:     │\n132:     ├─► Is it reference documentation?\n133:     │   └─► Create Skill instead\n134:     │\n135:     ├─► Is it reusable knowledge?\n136:     │   └─► Create Skill instead\n137:     │\n138:     └─► Is it one-time task?\n139:         └─► Just do it (no command needed)\n140: ```\n141: \n142: ### Command Types by Complexity\n143: \n144: | Type                  | Complexity | Lines       | Use When                                 |\n145: | --------------------- | ---------- | ----------- | ---------------------------------------- |\n146: | **Simple**            | Low        | 50-100      | Single action, few args                  |\n147: | **Workflow**          | Medium     | 100-200     | Multi-step process with outputs          |\n148: | **Mode-Based**        | Medium     | 150-250     | User controls execution pace             |\n149: | **Argument Dispatch** | Medium     | 150-300     | Multiple entry points/actions            |\n150: | **Destructive**       | Medium     | 100-180     | Irreversible actions, needs confirmation |\n151: | **Namespace**         | Varies     | 50-150 each | Related commands grouped together        |\n152: \n153: ---\n154: \n155: ## 3. COMMAND TYPES\n156: \n157: ### Overview\n158: \n159: | Type                  | Complexity | Use When                      | Template Section |\n160: | --------------------- | ---------- | ----------------------------- | ---------------- |\n161: | **Simple**            | Low        | Single action, few args       | Section 10       |\n162: | **Workflow**          | Medium     | Multi-step process            | Section 11       |\n163: | **Mode-Based**        | Medium     | `:auto`/`:confirm` variants   | Section 12       |\n164: | **Argument Dispatch** | Medium     | Multiple entry points/actions | Section 13       |\n165: | **Destructive**       | Medium     | Requires confirmation         | Section 14       |\n166: | **Namespace**         | Varies     | Grouped related commands      | Section 15       |\n167: \n168: ### Choosing the Right Type\n169: \n170: ```\n171: Start Here\n172:     │\n173:     ├─► Single action, straightforward?\n174:     │   └─► SIMPLE COMMAND\n175:     │\n176:     ├─► Multiple defined steps with outputs?\n177:     │   └─► WORKFLOW COMMAND\n178:     │\n179:     ├─► User should control execution pace?\n180:     │   └─► MODE-BASED COMMAND\n181:     │\n182:     ├─► Multiple action keywords (start/stop/status)?\n183:     │   └─► ARGUMENT DISPATCH\n184:     │\n185:     ├─► Deletes data or irreversible?\n186:     │   └─► DESTRUCTIVE COMMAND\n187:     │\n188:     └─► Part of related command group?\n189:         └─► NAMESPACE COMMAND\n190: ```\n191: \n192: ---\n193: \n194: ## 4. STANDARD COMMAND STRUCTURE\n195: \n196: ### Common Sections (All Command Types)\n197: \n198: | Order | Section             | Required         | Purpose                             |\n199: | ----- | ------------------- | ---------------- | ----------------------------------- |\n200: | 0     | **Frontmatter**     | Yes              | Metadata (description, args, tools) |\n201: | 1     | **Mandatory Gate**  | If required args | Prevent context inference           |\n202: | 2     | **Title + Purpose** | Yes              | What the command does               |\n203: | 3     | **Contract**        | Recommended      | Inputs/outputs specification        |\n204: | 4     | **Instructions**    | Yes              | Step-by-step execution              |\n205: | 5     | **Examples**        | Recommended      | Usage demonstrations                |\n206: | 6     | **Notes**           | Optional         | Caveats, requirements               |\n207: \n208: ### Minimal Command Structure\n209: \n210: ```markdown\n211: ---\n212: description: [Action verb] [what it does]\n213: argument-hint: \"<required> [optional]\"\n214: allowed-tools: Tool1, Tool2\n215: ---\n216: \n217: # Command Title\n218: \n219: [One sentence describing purpose.]\n220: \n221: ## 1. PURPOSE\n222: \n223: [2-3 sentences explaining the command.]\n224: \n225: ## 2. INSTRUCTIONS\n226: \n227: ### Step 1: [Name]\n228: [Instructions]\n229: \n230: ### Step 2: Return Status\n231: - Success: `STATUS=OK`\n232: - Failure: `STATUS=FAIL ERROR=\"<message>\"`\n233: ```\n234: \n235: ---\n236: \n237: ## 5. STEP NUMBERING RULES\n238: \n239: **Rule**: Use full integers only (1, 2, 3). No decimals (1.5, 2.5) or sub-steps (1.1, 1.2).\n240: \n241: | Element  | Correct                   | Wrong              |\n242: | -------- | ------------------------- | ------------------ |\n243: | Steps    | Step 1, Step 2, Step 3    | Step 1.5, Step 2.5 |\n244: | Phases   | PHASE 1, PHASE 2, PHASE 3 | PHASE 1.5, PHASE 2 |\n245: | Sections | ## 1. PURPOSE               | ## 1.1 PURPOSE     |\n246: \n247: **Sub-activities**: Use bullets within a step, not decimal sub-steps:\n248: ```markdown\n249: Step 3: Execute workflow\n250:   - Load configuration\n251:   - Validate inputs  \n252:   - Run process\n253: ```\n254: \n255: ---\n256: \n257: ## 6. SECTION VOCABULARY\n258: \n259: Commands use two categories of notation: **semantic markers** (for blocking/validation states) and **section names** (for content organization).\n260: \n261: ### Semantic Markers (Blocking/Validation)\n262: \n263: These markers indicate workflow state and enforcement:\n264: \n265: | Marker | Name    | Purpose                     | Example Usage               |\n266: | ------ | ------- | --------------------------- | --------------------------- |\n267: | MANDATORY | Alert   | Critical/mandatory sections | `# MANDATORY PHASES`      |\n268: | PHASE  | Lock    | Phase/gate headers          | `## PHASE 1: INPUT`       |\n269: | PASSED | Check   | Passed/success status       | `PASSED`                   |\n270: | N/A    | Skip    | N/A or skipped              | `N/A (no memory files)`    |\n271: | STOP   | Stop    | Hard stop/blocking error    | `STOP - Phase incomplete`  |\n272: | WARNING| Warning | Non-blocking alert          | `VIOLATION DETECTED`       |\n273: | FAILED | Fail    | Validation failure          | `FAILED`                   |\n274: \n275: ### Standard Section Names\n276: \n277: These names identify section types. Use EXACTLY as shown:\n278: \n279: | Section      | H2 Format                    | Purpose                      |\n280: | ------------ | ---------------------------- | ---------------------------- |\n281: | PURPOSE      | `## N. PURPOSE`              | What the command does        |\n282: | CONTRACT     | `## N. CONTRACT`             | Inputs/outputs specification |\n283: | WORKFLOW     | `## N. WORKFLOW OVERVIEW`    | Process flow/steps table     |\n284: | INSTRUCTIONS | `## N. INSTRUCTIONS`         | How to execute               |\n285: | REFERENCE    | `## N. REFERENCE`            | Related resources            |\n286: | EXAMPLES     | `## N. EXAMPLES`             | Usage demonstrations         |\n287: | RELATED      | `## N. RELATED COMMANDS`     | Links to related commands    |\n288: | TOOLS        | `## N. TOOL SIGNATURES`      | MCP/tool configuration       |\n289: | ROUTING      | `## N. ARGUMENT ROUTING`     | Mode detection/dispatch      |\n290: | DOCS         | `## N. FULL DOCUMENTATION`   | Link to full docs            |\n291: | INPUT        | `## N. USER INPUT`           | User input display           |\n292: \n293: ### Section Naming Rules\n294: \n295: 1. **One name per purpose**: Don't reuse section names across different purposes\n296: 2. **Consistent naming**: Use the same section name for the same purpose across commands\n297: 3. **Exact format**: `## N. SECTION-NAME` (number, period, space, name in ALL CAPS)\n298: \n299: ---\n300: \n301: ## 7. FRONTMATTER REFERENCE\n302: \n303: ### Required Fields\n304: \n305: ```yaml\n306: ---\n307: description: Clear, action-oriented single-line description shown in /help output. Start with action verb (Create, Search, Delete, Start, Stop).\n308: ---\n309: ```\n310: \n311: > **Important:** The `description` field MUST be a single-line string, not a YAML block scalar (`|` or `>`). Multi-line descriptions break `/help` output rendering.\n312: \n313: ### Recommended Fields\n314: \n315: ```yaml\n316: ---\n317: argument-hint: \"<required> [optional] [--flag]\"\n318: # Format conventions:\n319: #   <angle-brackets> = required argument\n320: #   [square-brackets] = optional argument\n321: #   --flag = boolean flag\n322: #   [default: value] = argument with default\n323: \n324: allowed-tools: Tool1, Tool2, Tool3\n325: # Common tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob, Task\n326: # MCP tools: mcp__[server-name]__[tool_function]\n327: ---\n328: ```\n329: \n330: ### Optional Fields\n331: \n332: ```yaml\n333: ---\n334: name: command-name\n335: # Override inferred name from filename\n336: \n337: model: opus\n338: # Override default model (USE SPARINGLY - only for complex reasoning)\n339: \n340: version: 1.0.0\n341: # Track command version\n342: \n343: disable-model-invocation: true\n344: # Prevent the AI agent from invoking this command\n345: ---\n346: ```\n347: \n348: ### Example\n349: \n350: ```yaml\n351: ---\n352: description: Complete spec folder workflow (5 steps) - research through implementation\n353: argument-hint: \"<task> [:auto|:confirm]\"\n354: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Task\n355: ---\n356: ```\n357: \n358: ---\n359: \n360: ## 8. MANDATORY GATE PATTERN (CRITICAL)\n361: \n362: ### Why This Pattern Exists\n363: \n364: Without this gate, AI agents may:\n365: - Infer tasks from conversation history or open files\n366: - Assume what the user wants based on screenshots or context\n367: - Proceed with incorrect assumptions instead of asking\n368: \n369: ### When to Use\n370: \n371: | Argument Type                  | Use Mandatory Gate? | Example                              |\n372: | ------------------------------ | ------------------- | ------------------------------------ |\n373: | `<required>` (angle brackets)  | **YES**             | `<task>`, `<query>`, `<spec-folder>` |\n374: | `[optional]` (square brackets) | No (has default)    | `[count]`, `[--flag]`                |\n375: | `[:auto\\|:confirm]` mode flags | No (mode selection) | Mode suffixes only                   |\n376: \n377: ### The Pattern\n378: \n379: Add this block **immediately after frontmatter, before any other content**:\n380: \n381: ```markdown\n382: # 🚨 MANDATORY FIRST ACTION - DO NOT SKIP\n383: \n384: **BEFORE READING ANYTHING ELSE IN THIS FILE, CHECK `$ARGUMENTS`:**\n385: \n386: \\`\\`\\`\n387: IF $ARGUMENTS is empty, undefined, or contains only whitespace (ignoring mode flags):\n388:     → STOP IMMEDIATELY\n389:     → Present the user with this question:\n390:         question: \"[Context-appropriate question]\"\n391:         options:\n392:           - label: \"[Action label]\"\n393:             description: \"[What user will provide]\"\n394:     → WAIT for user response\n395:     → Use their response as the [input type]\n396:     → Only THEN continue with this workflow\n397: \n398: IF $ARGUMENTS contains [expected input]:\n399:     → Continue reading this file\n400: \\`\\`\\`\n401: \n402: **CRITICAL RULES:**\n403: - **DO NOT** infer [input type] from context, screenshots, or existing files\n404: - **DO NOT** assume what the user wants based on conversation history\n405: - **DO NOT** proceed past this point without an explicit [input] from the user\n406: - The [input] MUST come from `$ARGUMENTS` or user's answer to the question above\n407: ```\n408: \n409: ### Example Questions by Command Type\n410: \n411: | Command Purpose    | Question                                          |\n412: | ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------- |\n413: | Planning           | \"What would you like to plan?\"                    |\n414: | Research           | \"What topic would you like to research?\"          |\n415: | Implementation     | \"Which spec folder would you like to implement?\"  |\n416: | File improvement   | \"What would you like to improve and which files?\" |\n417: | Prompt enhancement | \"What prompt would you like to improve?\"          |\n418: | Generic routing    | \"What request would you like to route?\"           |\n419: \n420: ### Multi-Phase Blocking Pattern\n421: \n422: For commands requiring multiple inputs before workflow execution:\n423: \n424: ```markdown\n425: # 🚨 MANDATORY PHASES - BLOCKING ENFORCEMENT\n426: \n427: > **HARD BLOCK**: Do not proceed past this section until ALL phases complete.\n428: \n429: ## PHASE 1: INPUT COLLECTION\n430: [Collect required inputs from $ARGUMENTS or prompt user]\n431: \n432: ## PHASE 2: CONTEXT VERIFICATION\n433: [Verify prerequisites exist]\n434: \n435: ## PHASE STATUS VERIFICATION (BLOCKING)\n436: \n437: | Phase            | Status | Blocker? |\n438: | ---------------- | ------ | -------- |\n439: | Input Collection | ✅/❌   | HARD     |\n440: | Context Verify   | ✅/❌   | HARD     |\n441: \n442: **Gate Check:** ALL phases must show ✅. ANY ❌ = STOP and resolve.\n443: ```\n444: \n445: ### Violation Self-Detection\n446: \n447: Every workflow command MUST include:\n448: \n449: ```markdown\n450: ## VIOLATION SELF-DETECTION (BLOCKING)\n451: \n452: **Before proceeding, verify you have NOT:**\n453: - [ ] Skipped any required phase\n454: - [ ] Used project tools before completing phases\n455: - [ ] Proceeded without required user confirmation\n456: \n457: **If ANY violation:** STOP → State violation → Return to phase → Complete properly\n458: ```\n459: \n460: ### Gate Exemption Declaration\n461: \n462: For commands exempt from Gate 3:\n463: \n464: ```markdown\n465: ## GATE 3 STATUS: EXEMPT\n466: \n467: | Aspect      | Value                            |\n468: | ----------- | -------------------------------- |\n469: | Location    | [Where output goes]              |\n470: | Reason      | [Why exempt]                     |\n471: | Alternative | [What replaces spec folder]      |\n472: ```\n473: \n474: ---\n475: \n476: ## 9. SIMPLE COMMAND TEMPLATE\n477: \n478: Use for: Single-action commands with straightforward execution.\n479: \n480: ```markdown\n481: ---\n482: description: [Action verb] [what it does] [context/scope]\n483: argument-hint: \"<required-arg> [optional-arg]\"\n484: allowed-tools: Tool1, Tool2\n485: ---\n486: \n487: # 🚨 MANDATORY FIRST ACTION - DO NOT SKIP\n488: \n489: **BEFORE READING ANYTHING ELSE IN THIS FILE, CHECK `$ARGUMENTS`:**\n490: \n491: \\`\\`\\`\n492: IF $ARGUMENTS is empty, undefined, or contains only whitespace:\n493:     → STOP IMMEDIATELY\n494:     → Present options to user\n495:     → WAIT for user response\n496:     → Only THEN continue\n497: \n498: IF $ARGUMENTS contains required input:\n499:     → Continue reading this file\n500: \\`\\`\\`\n501: \n502: **CRITICAL RULES:**\n503: - **DO NOT** infer from context, screenshots, or conversation history\n504: - **DO NOT** assume what the user wants\n505: - **DO NOT** proceed without explicit input from the user\n506: \n507: ---\n508: \n509: # [Command Title]\n510: \n511: [One sentence describing what this command does and when to use it.]\n512: \n513: ---\n514: \n515: ## 1. PURPOSE\n516: \n517: [2-3 sentences explaining the command's purpose and primary use case.]\n518: \n519: ---\n520: \n521: ## 2. CONTRACT\n522: \n523: **Inputs:** `$ARGUMENTS` — [Description of expected arguments]\n524: **Outputs:** `STATUS=<OK|FAIL> [ADDITIONAL_DATA=<value>]`\n525: \n526: ---\n527: \n528: ## 3. INSTRUCTIONS\n529: \n530: Execute the following steps:\n531: \n532: ### Step 1: [Step Name]\n533: \n534: - [Sub-step or detail]\n535: - [Sub-step or detail]\n536: \n537: ### Step 2: [Step Name]\n538: \n539: - [Sub-step or detail]\n540: \n541: ### Step 3: Return Status\n542: \n543: - If successful: `STATUS=OK [DATA=<value>]`\n544: - If failed: `STATUS=FAIL ERROR=\"<message>\"`\n545: \n546: ---\n547: \n548: ## 4. EXAMPLE USAGE\n549: \n550: ### Basic Usage\n551: \n552: \\`\\`\\`bash\n553: /command-name \"argument\"\n554: \\`\\`\\`\n555: \n556: ### With Optional Args\n557: \n558: \\`\\`\\`bash\n559: /command-name \"argument\" --flag\n560: \\`\\`\\`\n561: \n562: ---\n563: \n564: ## 5. EXAMPLE OUTPUT\n565: \n566: \\`\\`\\`\n567: [Formatted output example]\n568: \n569: STATUS=OK DATA=<value>\n570: \\`\\`\\`\n571: \n572: ---\n573: \n574: ## 6. NOTES\n575: \n576: - **[Category]:** [Important note about usage]\n577: - **[Category]:** [Performance or limitation note]\n578: - **Requirements:** [Prerequisites or dependencies]\n579: ```\n580: \n581: ### Simple Command Example\n582: \n583: ```yaml\n584: ---\n585: description: Search codebase semantically using natural language queries\n586: argument-hint: \"<query> [--refined]\"\n587: allowed-tools: mcp__semantic-search__semantic_search\n588: ---\n589: ```\n590: \n591: ---\n592: \n593: ## 10. WORKFLOW COMMAND TEMPLATE\n594: \n595: Use for: Multi-step processes with defined phases and outputs.\n596: \n597: ```markdown\n598: ---\n599: description: [Workflow name] ([N] steps) - [brief purpose]\n600: argument-hint: \"<topic> [context]\"\n601: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Task\n602: ---\n603: \n604: # 🚨 MANDATORY FIRST ACTION - DO NOT SKIP\n605: \n606: [Include mandatory gate pattern from Section 6]\n607: \n608: ---\n609: \n610: # [Workflow Title]\n611: \n612: **Purpose**: [One sentence describing the workflow's goal and primary output.]\n613: \n614: ---\n615: \n616: ## 1. USER INPUT\n617: \n618: \\`\\`\\`text\n619: $ARGUMENTS\n620: \\`\\`\\`\n621: \n622: ---\n623: \n624: ## 2. WORKFLOW OVERVIEW ([N] STEPS)\n625: \n626: | Step | Name         | Purpose               | Outputs             |\n627: | ---- | ------------ | --------------------- | ------------------- |\n628: | 1    | [Step Name]  | [What it does]        | [Artifacts created] |\n629: | 2    | [Step Name]  | [What it does]        | [Artifacts created] |\n630: | 3    | [Step Name]  | [What it does]        | [Artifacts created] |\n631: | N    | Save Context | Preserve conversation | memory/*.md         |\n632: \n633: ---\n634: \n635: ## 3. INSTRUCTIONS\n636: \n637: ### Step 1: [Step Name]\n638: \n639: [Detailed instructions for this step]\n640: \n641: **Validation checkpoint:**\n642: - [ ] [Condition that must be true]\n643: - [ ] [Another condition]\n644: \n645: ### Step 2: [Step Name]\n646: \n647: [Detailed instructions for this step]\n648: \n649: ---\n650: \n651: ## 4. FAILURE RECOVERY\n652: \n653: | Failure Type        | Recovery Action  |\n654: | ------------------- | ---------------- |\n655: | [Failure condition] | [How to recover] |\n656: | [Another condition] | [Recovery steps] |\n657: \n658: ---\n659: \n660: ## 5. ERROR HANDLING\n661: \n662: | Condition          | Action                            |\n663: | ------------------ | --------------------------------- |\n664: | Empty `$ARGUMENTS` | Prompt user: \"Please describe...\" |\n665: | [Other condition]  | [Action to take]                  |\n666: \n667: ---\n668: \n669: ## 6. TEMPLATES USED\n670: \n671: - `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/templates/[template].md`\n672: - [Other template references]\n673: \n674: ---\n675: \n676: ## 7. COMPLETION REPORT\n677: \n678: After workflow completion, report:\n679: \n680: \\`\\`\\`\n681: ✅ [Workflow Name] Complete\n682: \n683: [Summary of what was accomplished]\n684: \n685: Artifacts Created:\n686: - [artifact 1]\n687: - [artifact 2]\n688: \n689: Next Steps:\n690: - [Recommended follow-up action]\n691: \\`\\`\\`\n692: \n693: ---\n694: \n695: ## 8. EXAMPLES\n696: \n697: **Example 1: [Use case]**\n698: \\`\\`\\`\n699: /workflow-name [arguments]\n700: \\`\\`\\`\n701: \n702: **Example 2: [Another use case]**\n703: \\`\\`\\`\n704: /workflow-name [different arguments]\n705: \\`\\`\\`\n706: ```\n707: \n708: ---\n709: \n710: ## 11. MODE-BASED COMMAND TEMPLATE\n711: \n712: Use for: Commands supporting `:auto` and `:confirm` execution modes.\n713: \n714: ```markdown\n715: ---\n716: description: [Workflow name] ([N] steps) - [purpose]. Supports :auto and :confirm modes\n717: argument-hint: \"<request> [:auto|:confirm]\"\n718: allowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Task\n719: ---\n720: \n721: # 🚨 MANDATORY FIRST ACTION - DO NOT SKIP\n722: \n723: [Include mandatory gate pattern from Section 6]\n724: \n725: ---\n726: \n727: # [Command Title]\n728: \n729: **Purpose**: [Description of what this command accomplishes.]\n730: \n731: ---\n732: \n733: ## 1. USER INPUT\n734: \n735: \\`\\`\\`text\n736: $ARGUMENTS\n737: \\`\\`\\`\n738: \n739: ---\n740: \n741: ## 2. MODE DETECTION & ROUTING\n742: \n743: ### Step 1: Parse Mode Suffix\n744: \n745: Detect execution mode from command invocation:\n746: \n747: | Pattern                | Mode        | Behavior                                      |\n748: | ---------------------- | ----------- | --------------------------------------------- |\n749: | `/command:auto`        | AUTONOMOUS  | Execute all steps without user approval gates |\n750: | `/command:confirm`     | INTERACTIVE | Pause at each step for user approval          |\n751: | `/command` (no suffix) | PROMPT      | Ask user to choose mode                       |\n752: \n753: ### Step 2: Mode Selection (when no suffix detected)\n754: \n755: If no `:auto` or `:confirm` suffix is present, present options to user:\n756: \n757: **Question**: \"How would you like to execute this workflow?\"\n758: \n759: | Option | Mode        | Description                                                    |\n760: | ------ | ----------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |\n761: | **A**  | Autonomous  | Execute all steps without approval gates. Best for [use case]. |\n762: | **B**  | Interactive | Pause at each step for approval. Best for [use case].          |\n763: \n764: **Wait for user response before proceeding.**\n765: \n766: ### Step 3: Transform Raw Input\n767: \n768: Parse the raw text from `$ARGUMENTS` and transform into structured fields.\n769: \n770: ---\n771: \n772: ## 3. KEY BEHAVIORS\n773: \n774: ### Autonomous Mode (`:auto`)\n775: - Executes all steps without user approval gates\n776: - Self-validates at each checkpoint\n777: - Makes informed decisions based on best judgment\n778: - Documents all significant decisions\n779: \n780: ### Interactive Mode (`:confirm`)\n781: - Pauses after each step for user approval\n782: - Presents options: Approve, Review Details, Modify, Skip, Abort\n783: - Documents user decisions at each checkpoint\n784: - Allows course correction throughout workflow\n785: \n786: ---\n787: \n788: ## 4. CONTEXT LOADING\n789: \n790: When resuming work in an existing spec folder, prompt to load prior session memory:\n791: - **A)** Load most recent memory file (quick context refresh)\n792: - **B)** Load all recent files (up to 3) (comprehensive context)\n793: - **C)** List all files and select specific (historical search)\n794: - **D)** Skip (start fresh, no context)\n795: \n796: ---\n797: \n798: ## 5. EXAMPLES\n799: \n800: **Example 1: Autonomous execution**\n801: \\`\\`\\`\n802: /command:auto [arguments]\n803: \\`\\`\\`\n804: \n805: **Example 2: Interactive execution**\n806: \\`\\`\\`\n807: /command:confirm [arguments]\n808: \\`\\`\\`\n809: \n810: **Example 3: Prompt for mode selection**\n811: \\`\\`\\`\n812: /command [arguments]\n813: \\`\\`\\`\n814: ```\n815: \n816: ### Presentation / Router Split (Command Families)\n817: \n818: The memory, speckit, create, doctor, and deep command families split each command into a **thin router** plus **owned assets**, so routing logic and presentation contracts evolve independently and long command files stay readable.\n819: \n820: **Common core — all split families:**\n821: \n822: | Asset | Owns |\n823: |-------|------|\n824: | `<command>.md` (thin router) | Mode resolution, owned-assets table, routing logic, and any Phase 0 / mandatory-input gate. Contains NO presentation content. |\n825: | `assets/<ns>_<command>_presentation.txt` | Startup prompts, dashboards and checkpoints, result templates, and next-step wording. The display source of truth. |\n826: \n827: - The router contains a **Presentation Boundary** section naming what lives only in the presentation asset; it must contain no inline startup-question wording, dashboard templates, or result templates. The split is behavior-preserving — relocate display content, never change routing semantics.\n828: - In `allowed-tools`, MCP tools use the fully-qualified `mcp__<server>__<tool>` form (e.g. `mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_context`), matching the `opencode.json` MCP namespace. Bare tool IDs (e.g. `memory_context`) belong in instruction prose, never in `allowed-tools`.\n829: \n830: **Workflow-backed families (speckit, create, deep)** additionally own `:auto` / `:confirm` workflow YAML that the router routes modes to:\n831: \n832: | Asset | Owns |\n833: |-------|------|\n834: | `assets/<ns>_<command>_auto.yaml` | Autonomous-mode workflow: steps, agent dispatch, artifact writes. |\n835: | `assets/<ns>_<command>_confirm.yaml` | Interactive-mode workflow. |\n836: \n837: The **memory** and **doctor** families have NO workflow YAML — their routers dispatch directly to tools and scripts.\n838: \n839: **Canonical router shape (first-class standard).** Every router uses one canonical, numbered section vocabulary — full integers, in this order: **`## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT`**, **`## 2. OWNED ASSETS`**, **`## 3. MODE ROUTING`**, **`## 4. EXECUTION TARGETS`**, **`## 5. PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`**, **`## 6. WORKFLOW SUMMARY`**. The blocking core is only `Owned Assets` + `Presentation Boundary`; the other four are recommended and surface as non-blocking warnings when absent. Variants differ by hand-off only, not by required sections:\n840: \n841: - **Workflow-YAML-backed** (speckit, create, deep-large) route modes into `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`.\n842: - **Direct-dispatch-script** (memory, doctor, skill-benchmark) dispatch straight to tools and scripts and may leave the recommended sections as warnings.\n843: - **Compiled-stub** commands carry a `render-command-contract` marker and are exempt from section requirements (retained variant; no command currently uses it — the deep commands are full routers).\n844: \n845: Do not invent divergent synonyms (`Routing Assets`, `Workflow Routing`, `Execution Order`); the validator alias-normalizes those as a safety net, but the authored end state is the canonical names above. Reference shape: `.opencode/commands/speckit/plan.md` (router) + `speckit_plan_presentation.txt` (contract). Skeletons: [`command_router_template.md`](command_router_template.md), [`command_presentation_template.md`](command_presentation_template.md).\n846: \n847: ---\n848: \n849: ## 12. ARGUMENT DISPATCH PATTERN\n850: \n851: Use for: Commands that accept multiple argument types and need to route to different actions.\n852: \n853: ### Pattern Overview\n854: \n855: When a single command handles multiple argument patterns (like `/semantic_search` accepting queries, actions, and flags), use an ASCII decision tree to document the routing logic clearly.\n856: \n857: ### When to Use Argument Dispatch\n858: \n859: | Scenario                                   | Use Pattern?                 |\n860: | ------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------- |\n861: | Command has multiple action keywords       | **Yes**                      |\n862: | Command accepts both keywords AND queries  | **Yes**                      |\n863: | Command has only one action                | No (use simple template)     |\n864: | Command uses `:auto`/`:confirm` modes only | No (use mode-based template) |\n865: \n866: ### The Pattern\n867: \n868: ```markdown\n869: ---\n870: description: [Command] with multiple entry points\n871: argument-hint: \"[action|query] [options]\"\n872: allowed-tools: [Tools]\n873: ---\n874: \n875: # [Command Title]\n876: \n877: ---\n878: \n879: ## 1. ARGUMENT DISPATCH\n880: \n881: \\`\\`\\`\n882: $ARGUMENTS\n883:     │\n884:     ├─► Empty (no args)\n885:     │   └─► DEFAULT ACTION: [What happens with no args]\n886:     │\n887:     ├─► First word matches ACTION KEYWORD (case-insensitive)\n888:     │   ├─► \"start\" | \"on\" | \"init\"       → START ACTION\n889:     │   ├─► \"stop\" | \"off\" | \"kill\"       → STOP ACTION\n890:     │   ├─► \"status\" | \"info\"             → STATUS ACTION\n891:     │   ├─► \"search\" | \"find\" | \"query\"   → SEARCH ACTION (remaining args = query)\n892:     │   └─► \"reset\" | \"clear\"             → RESET ACTION\n893:     │\n894:     ├─► Looks like NATURAL LANGUAGE QUERY\n895:     │   Detection: 2+ words, question words, code terms, quotes\n896:     │   └─► SEARCH ACTION (full args = query)\n897:     │\n898:     └─► Single ambiguous word\n899:         └─► [DEFAULT ACTION] (assume most common intent)\n900: \\`\\`\\`\n901: \n902: ---\n903: \n904: ## 2. ACTION HANDLERS\n905: \n906: ### START ACTION\n907: [Instructions for start]\n908: \n909: ### STOP ACTION\n910: [Instructions for stop]\n911: \n912: ### SEARCH ACTION\n913: [Instructions for search]\n914: \n915: ---\n916: \n917: ## 3. EXAMPLE ROUTING\n918: \n919: | Input                | Detected As      | Action                  |\n920: | -------------------- | ---------------- | ----------------------- |\n921: | (empty)              | No args          | Show menu/help          |\n922: | `start`              | Keyword          | START ACTION            |\n923: | `how does auth work` | Natural language | SEARCH ACTION           |\n924: | `oauth`              | Single word      | SEARCH ACTION (default) |\n925: ```\n926: \n927: ### Real Example: `/semantic_search`\n928: \n929: ```\n930: /semantic_search [args]\n931:     │\n932:     ├─► No args\n933:     │   └─► Show usage help\n934:     │\n935:     ├─► \"index\" | \"reindex\" | \"rebuild\"\n936:     │   └─► INDEX ACTION: Rebuild vector index\n937:     │\n938:     ├─► \"status\" | \"health\"\n939:     │   └─► STATUS ACTION: Show index health\n940:     │\n941:     ├─► Natural language query (2+ words)\n942:     │   └─► SEARCH ACTION: Execute semantic search\n943:     │\n944:     └─► Single ambiguous word\n945:         └─► SEARCH ACTION (assume search intent)\n946: ```\n947: \n948: ### Combining with Mode-Based Pattern\n949: \n950: For commands that need BOTH argument dispatch AND mode support:\n951: \n952: ```\n953: $ARGUMENTS\n954:     │\n955:     ├─► Parse mode suffix (:auto | :confirm)\n956:     │\n957:     └─► After mode extraction, dispatch remaining args:\n958:         ├─► \"action1\" → ACTION 1\n959:         ├─► \"action2\" → ACTION 2\n960:         └─► Natural language → DEFAULT ACTION\n961: ```\n962: \n963: ---\n964: \n965: ## 13. DESTRUCTIVE COMMAND TEMPLATE\n966: \n967: Use for: Commands that delete data or make irreversible changes.\n968: \n969: ```markdown\n970: ---\n971: description: [Action] (DESTRUCTIVE)\n972: argument-hint: \"[--confirm]\"\n973: allowed-tools: Bash\n974: ---\n975: \n976: # [Command Title]\n977: \n978: **DESTRUCTIVE OPERATION** - [Brief warning about what will be affected.]\n979: \n980: ---\n981: \n982: ## 1. PURPOSE\n983: \n984: [Explain the destructive action and why it might be needed.]\n985: \n986: ---\n987: \n988: ## 2. CONTRACT\n989: \n990: **Inputs:** `$ARGUMENTS` — Must include `--confirm` flag to skip prompt\n991: **Outputs:** `STATUS=<OK|FAIL|CANCELLED> ACTION=<action|cancelled>`\n992: \n993: ---\n994: \n995: ## 3. INSTRUCTIONS\n996: \n997: ### Step 1: Safety Check - Require Confirmation\n998: \n999: - Check if `--confirm` flag is present in `$ARGUMENTS`\n1000: - If NOT present:\n1001:   - Ask user: \"[Warning message]. Are you sure?\"\n1002:   - Options: \"Yes, proceed\" / \"No, cancel\"\n1003:   - If user cancels: `STATUS=CANCELLED ACTION=cancelled`\n1004: \n1005: ### Step 2: Show What Will Be Affected\n1006: \n1007: - Display current state\n1008: - List items that will be deleted/changed\n1009: - Show size/count of affected data\n1010: \n1011: ### Step 3: Execute Destructive Action\n1012: \n1013: - [Step-by-step execution]\n1014: - Log each action taken\n1015: \n1016: ### Step 4: Verify Completion\n1017: \n1018: - Confirm action completed\n1019: - Show new state\n1020: \n1021: ### Step 5: Provide Recovery Guidance\n1022: \n1023: - Explain how to rebuild/restore if needed\n1024: - Link to relevant commands\n1025: \n1026: ### Step 6: Return Status\n1027: \n1028: - If completed: `STATUS=OK ACTION=[action]`\n1029: - If cancelled: `STATUS=CANCELLED ACTION=cancelled`\n1030: - If failed: `STATUS=FAIL ERROR=\"<message>\"`\n1031: \n1032: ---\n1033: \n1034: ## 4. EXAMPLE USAGE\n1035: \n1036: ### Without Confirmation (Safe Default)\n1037: \n1038: \\`\\`\\`bash\n1039: /command-name\n1040: \\`\\`\\`\n1041: → Will prompt for confirmation before proceeding\n1042: \n1043: ### With Confirmation Flag (Skip Prompt)\n1044: \n1045: \\`\\`\\`bash\n1046: /command-name --confirm\n1047: \\`\\`\\`\n1048: → Proceeds immediately (use with caution)\n1049: \n1050: ---\n1051: \n1052: ## 5. NOTES\n1053: \n1054: - **When to Use:**\n1055:   - [Valid use case 1]\n1056:   - [Valid use case 2]\n1057: \n1058: - **Impact:**\n1059:   - [What will be lost]\n1060:   - [Other consequences]\n1061:   - [What is preserved]\n1062:   - [Recovery options]\n1063: \n1064: - **Alternatives to Consider:**\n1065:   - [Less destructive alternative]\n1066:   - [Another option]\n1067: \n1068: ---\n1069: \n1070: ## 6. SAFETY FEATURES\n1071: \n1072: - Requires explicit confirmation by default\n1073: - Shows what will be affected before proceeding\n1074: - Provides clear recovery steps\n1075: - Cannot accidentally affect [protected items]\n1076: ```\n1077: \n1078: ---\n1079: \n1080: ## 14. NAMESPACE COMMAND PATTERN\n1081: \n1082: Use for: Grouping related commands under a common prefix.\n1083: \n1084: ### Directory Structure\n1085: \n1086: ```\n1087: .opencode/commands/\n1088: └── [namespace]/           # Directory name = namespace\n1089:     ├── [action1].md       # → /namespace:action1\n1090:     ├── [action2].md       # → /namespace:action2\n1091:     └── [action3].md       # → /namespace:action3\n1092: ```\n1093: \n1094: ### Example: Index Namespace\n1095: \n1096: ```\n1097: .opencode/commands/\n1098: └── index/\n1099:     ├── start.md     → /index:start\n1100:     ├── stop.md      → /index:stop\n1101:     ├── search.md    → /index:search\n1102:     ├── stats.md     → /index:stats\n1103:     ├── history.md   → /index:history\n1104:     └── reset.md     → /index:reset\n1105: ```\n1106: \n1107: ### Naming Conventions\n1108: \n1109: | Element             | Convention             | Example                      |\n1110: | ------------------- | ---------------------- | ---------------------------- |\n1111: | Namespace directory | lowercase, hyphen-case | `index/`, `git-workflow/`    |\n1112: | Action files        | lowercase, hyphen-case | `search.md`, `full-reset.md` |\n1113: | Resulting command   | namespace:action       | `/index:search`              |\n1114: \n1115: ---\n1116: \n1117: ## 15. VALIDATION CHECKLIST\n1118: \n1119: Before publishing a command, verify:\n1120: \n1121: ### Frontmatter\n1122: \n1123: - [ ] `description` is present and action-oriented\n1124: - [ ] `argument-hint` shows expected format (if args expected)\n1125: - [ ] `allowed-tools` lists all tools used (if any)\n1126: - [ ] No angle brackets `< >` in description (reserved for hints)\n1127: \n1128: ### Mandatory Gate (CRITICAL for required arguments)\n1129: \n1130: - [ ] If `argument-hint` contains `<required>` args → **MANDATORY GATE present**\n1131: - [ ] Gate is **immediately after frontmatter**, before any other content\n1132: - [ ] Gate presents options to user with appropriate question\n1133: - [ ] Gate includes all 4 CRITICAL RULES (DO NOT infer, assume, proceed)\n1134: - [ ] Skip gate only if ALL arguments are `[optional]` with defaults\n1135: \n1136: ### Structure\n1137: \n1138: - [ ] H1 title matches command purpose\n1139: - [ ] H2 sections use format: `## N. SECTION-NAME` (see Section 6 for section vocabulary)\n1140: - [ ] H3 subsections: `### Step N: Description`\n1141: - [ ] Dividers (`---`) between major sections\n1142: - [ ] Instructions are numbered and actionable\n1143: - [ ] Example usage shows 2-3 scenarios\n1144: - [ ] Full integer step numbering only (no 1.5, 2.5 - see Section 5)\n1145: \n1146: ### Header Format\n1147: \n1148: - [ ] H1: Plain title only (`# Command Title`) or with semantic emoji for blocking sections (`# 🚨 MANDATORY PHASES`)\n1149: - [ ] H2: Numbered + SECTION-NAME (`## 1. PURPOSE`)\n1150: - [ ] H3/H4: Title case (`### Step 1: Description`)\n1151: - [ ] Consistent numbering (1, 2, 3...)\n1152: - [ ] Section names from approved vocabulary (Section 6)\n1153: \n1154: **Blocking Phase Pattern:**\n1155: Commands with mandatory input phases use these semantic markers:\n1156: - `# MANDATORY PHASES` - Critical blocking section (H1)\n1157: - `## PHASE N:` - Required blocking phases (H2)\n1158: - `## PHASE STATUS VERIFICATION` - Gate checks (H2)\n1159: - `## VIOLATION SELF-DETECTION` - Violation recovery (H2)\n1160: \n1161: ---\n1162: \n1163: ## 16. ORCHESTRATOR + WORKERS PATTERN\n1164: \n1165: Use for: Commands that spawn parallel sub-agents for exploration/analysis.\n1166: \n1167: ```\n1168: OPUS ORCHESTRATOR → Dispatches → SONNET WORKERS (parallel)\n1169:      │                              │\n1170:      └── Synthesizes ←──────────────┘\n1171: ```\n1172: \n1173: | Role             | Model    | Responsibility                                        |\n1174: | ---------------- | -------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |\n1175: | **Orchestrator** | `opus`   | Task understanding, dispatch, verification, synthesis |\n1176: | **Workers**      | `sonnet` | Fast parallel exploration, hypothesis generation      |\n1177: \n1178: **Use when**: Parallel codebase exploration, multi-aspect analysis, complex planning.\n1179: **Skip when**: Simple single-action commands, sequential workflows.\n1180: \n1181: ---\n1182: \n1183: ## 17. STATUS OUTPUT PATTERNS\n1184: \n1185: ### Standard Patterns\n1186: \n1187: | Pattern                                 | Use Case       | Example              |\n1188: | --------------------------------------- | -------------- | -------------------- |\n1189: | `STATUS=OK`                             | Simple success | Basic commands       |\n1190: | `STATUS=OK RESULTS_COUNT=N`             | Search/query   | `/index:search`      |\n1191: | `STATUS=OK ACTION=<action>`             | State change   | `/index:start`       |\n1192: | `STATUS=OK ACTION=<action> PATH=<path>` | File creation  | `/speckit:complete` |\n1193: | `STATUS=FAIL ERROR=\"<message>\"`         | All failures   | Error handling       |\n1194: | `STATUS=CANCELLED ACTION=cancelled`     | User abort     | Interactive commands |\n1195: \n1196: ---\n1197: \n1198: ## 18. BEST PRACTICES SUMMARY\n1199: \n1200: ### DO\n1201: \n1202: | Practice                                 | Reason                            |\n1203: | ---------------------------------------- | --------------------------------- |\n1204: | Include mandatory gate for required args | Prevents context inference errors |\n1205: | Use action verbs in descriptions         | Clear, scannable in /help         |\n1206: | Document all steps with checkpoints      | Enables debugging and recovery    |\n1207: | Provide example usage                    | Users learn faster                |\n1208: | Return structured status                 | Enables automation                |\n1209: | Use appropriate command type             | Right tool for the job            |\n1210: \n1211: ### DON'T\n1212: \n1213: | Anti-Pattern               | Problem                      |\n1214: | -------------------------- | ---------------------------- |\n1215: | Skip mandatory gate        | AI will infer incorrectly    |\n1216: | Vague descriptions         | Users won't know when to use |\n1217: | Missing error handling     | Failures become mysterious   |\n1218: | No examples                | Users struggle to start      |\n1219: | Inconsistent status format | Breaks automation            |\n1220: | Over-complex commands      | Split into namespace instead |\n1221: \n1222: ---\n1223: \n1224: ## 19. RELATED RESOURCES\n1225: \n1226: ### Templates\n1227: - [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) - Frontmatter by document type\n1228: - [skill_md_template.md](../../../create-skill/assets/skill/skill_md_template.md) - If converting to skill\n1229: \n1230: ### Standards\n1231: - [core_standards.md](../../../shared/references/core_standards.md) - Document type rules\n1232: - [validation.md](../../../shared/references/validation.md) - Quality scoring\n\n(End of file - total 1232 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Command Template - OpenCode Slash Commands\ndescription: Templates and best practices for creating production-quality slash commands in OpenCode with proper frontmatter and structure.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"slash command template\"\n  - \"command frontmatter structure\"\n  - \"opencode command scaffold\"\n  - \"argument hint patterns\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.20\n---\n\n# Command Template - OpenCode Slash Commands\n\nTemplates for creating slash commands with proper frontmatter, mandatory gates, and structured workflows.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_template.md","text":"---\ntitle: Command Template - OpenCode Slash Commands\ndescription: Templates and best practices for creating production-quality slash commands in OpenCode with proper frontmatter and structure.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"slash command template\"\n  - \"command frontmatter structure\"\n  - \"opencode command scaffold\"\n  - \"argument hint patterns\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.8.0.20\n---\n\n# Command Template - OpenCode Slash Commands\n\nTemplates for creating slash commands with proper frontmatter, mandatory gates, and structured workflows.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### What Are OpenCode Commands?\n\n**OpenCode commands** are slash-triggered instructions (e.g., `/speckit:complete`, `/memory:save`) that automate workflows, enforce patterns, and extend AI agent capabilities. They're markdown files that define structured behavior for specific tasks.\n\n**Core Purpose**:\n- **Workflow automation** - Multi-step processes become single invocations\n- **Pattern enforcement** - Consistent behavior across sessions\n- **Task routing** - Arguments dispatch to appropriate handlers\n- **User guidance** - Structured prompts prevent errors\n- **Tool restriction** - Limit which tools the command can use\n\n**Key Difference from Skills**:\n- Commands = Actionable workflows triggered by `/command-name`\n- Skills = Reference documentation loaded via `Read(\".opencode/skills/<skill-name>/SKILL.md\")`\n\n### Core Characteristics\n\n| Characteristic         | Description                                           |\n| ---------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Markdown-based**     | Human-readable instruction files                      |\n| **Frontmatter-driven** | Metadata controls behavior (description, args, tools) |\n| **Argument-aware**     | Parse and validate user input via `$ARGUMENTS`        |\n| **Status-reporting**   | Return structured outcomes (`STATUS=OK\\|FAIL`)        |\n| **Tool-restricted**    | `allowed-tools` limits available tools                |\n\n### How Commands Are Invoked\n\n```\nUser types: /command-name arguments\n                │           │\n                │           └─► Passed as $ARGUMENTS variable\n                │\n                └─► OpenCode finds .opencode/commands/command-name.md\n                    │\n                    ├─► Loads frontmatter (description, tools, hints)\n                    │\n                    ├─► Injects $ARGUMENTS into instruction body\n                    │\n                    └─► AI agent executes instructions step-by-step\n```\n\n> **Description budget**: command `description:` fields share the Claude Code skill-metadata budget (default 8,000 chars total). Keep each command description **≤ 110 chars**, retain `:auto`/`:confirm` mode suffixes (advisor trigger tokens), no product enumerations. See [`assets/frontmatter_templates.md` § Description Budget & Trim Style](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) for the canonical trim rules.\n\n### Command File Location\n\n```\n.opencode/\n└── command/\n    ├── simple-command.md          → /simple-command\n    ├── workflow-command.md        → /workflow-command\n    └── namespace/                  → Grouped commands\n        ├── action1.md             → /namespace:action1\n        └── action2.md             → /namespace:action2\n```\n\n### Progressive Complexity\n\n```\nLevel 1: Simple Command\n         └─ Single action, few arguments (~50-100 lines)\n            ↓\nLevel 2: Workflow Command\n         └─ Multi-step process with validation (~100-200 lines)\n            ↓\nLevel 3: Mode-Based / Dispatch Command\n         └─ Complex routing, user control (~150-300 lines)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. WHEN TO CREATE COMMANDS\n\n### Create Command When\n\n- Multi-step process with defined phases\n- Repeated task needing consistency across sessions\n- Requires confirmation gates (destructive actions)\n- Multiple argument patterns need routing\n- User should control execution pace (`:auto`/`:confirm` modes)\n- Tool restrictions needed for security/focus\n\n### Use Skill Instead When\n\n- Content is reference material, not executable workflow\n- Complex domain knowledge that multiple commands might need\n- Reusable patterns/standards across multiple commands\n\n### Decision Framework\n\n```\nIs this a repeatable workflow with defined steps?\n├─► YES\n│   │\n│   ├─► Does it need user arguments?\n│   │   └─► Command with argument-hint + mandatory gate\n│   │\n│   ├─► Does it have modes (auto/confirm)?\n│   │   └─► Mode-based command template\n│   │\n│   ├─► Is it destructive/irreversible?\n│   │   └─► Destructive command template\n│   │\n│   ├─► Multiple action keywords (start/stop/status)?\n│   │   └─► Argument dispatch pattern\n│   │\n│   └─► Simple single action?\n│       └─► Simple command template\n│\n└─► NO\n    │\n    ├─► Is it reference documentation?\n    │   └─► Create Skill instead\n    │\n    ├─► Is it reusable knowledge?\n    │   └─► Create Skill instead\n    │\n    └─► Is it one-time task?\n        └─► Just do it (no command needed)\n```\n\n### Command Types by Complexity\n\n| Type                  | Complexity | Lines       | Use When                                 |\n| --------------------- | ---------- | ----------- | ---------------------------------------- |\n| **Simple**            | Low        | 50-100      | Single action, few args                  |\n| **Workflow**          | Medium     | 100-200     | Multi-step process with outputs          |\n| **Mode-Based**        | Medium     | 150-250     | User controls execution pace             |\n| **Argument Dispatch** | Medium     | 150-300     | Multiple entry points/actions            |\n| **Destructive**       | Medium     | 100-180     | Irreversible actions, needs confirmation |\n| **Namespace**         | Varies     | 50-150 each | Related commands grouped together        |\n\n---\n\n## 3. COMMAND TYPES\n\n### Overview\n\n| Type                  | Complexity | Use When                      | Template Section |\n| --------------------- | ---------- | ----------------------------- | ---------------- |\n| **Simple**            | Low        | Single action, few args       | Section 10       |\n| **Workflow**          | Medium     | Multi-step process            | Section 11       |\n| **Mode-Based**        | Medium     | `:auto`/`:confirm` variants   | Section 12       |\n| **Argument Dispatch** | Medium     | Multiple entry points/actions | Section 13       |\n| **Destructive**       | Medium     | Requires confirmation         | Section 14       |\n| **Namespace**         | Varies     | Grouped related commands      | Section 15       |\n\n### Choosing the Right Type\n\n```\nStart Here\n    │\n    ├─► Single action, straightforward?\n    │   └─► SIMPLE COMMAND\n    │\n    ├─► Multiple defined steps with outputs?\n    │   └─► WORKFLOW COMMAND\n    │\n    ├─► User should control execution pace?\n    │   └─► MODE-BASED COMMAND\n    │\n    ├─► Multiple action keywords (start/stop/status)?\n    │   └─► ARGUMENT DISPATCH\n    │\n    ├─► Deletes data or irreversible?\n    │   └─► DESTRUCTIVE COMMAND\n    │\n    └─► Part of related command group?\n        └─► NAMESPACE COMMAND\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. STANDARD COMMAND STRUCTURE\n\n### Common Sections (All Command Types)\n\n| Order | Section             | Required         | Purpose                             |\n| ----- | ------------------- | ---------------- | ----------------------------------- |\n| 0     | **Frontmatter**     | Yes              | Metadata (description, args, tools) |\n| 1     | **Mandatory Gate**  | If required args | Prevent context inference           |\n| 2     | **Title + Purpose** | Yes              | What the command does               |\n| 3     | **Contract**        | Recommended      | Inputs/outputs specification        |\n| 4     | **Instructions**    | Yes              | Step-by-step execution              |\n| 5     | **Examples**        | Recommended      | Usage demonstrations                |\n| 6     | **Notes**           | Optional         | Caveats, requirements               |\n\n### Minimal Command Structure\n\n```markdown\n---\ndescription: [Action verb] [what it does]\nargument-hint: \"<required> [optional]\"\nallowed-tools: Tool1, Tool2\n---\n\n# Command Title\n\n[One sentence describing purpose.]\n\n## 1. PURPOSE\n\n[2-3 sentences explaining the command.]\n\n## 2. INSTRUCTIONS\n\n### Step 1: [Name]\n[Instructions]\n\n### Step 2: Return Status\n- Success: `STATUS=OK`\n- Failure: `STATUS=FAIL ERROR=\"<message>\"`\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. STEP NUMBERING RULES\n\n**Rule**: Use full integers only (1, 2, 3). No decimals (1.5, 2.5) or sub-steps (1.1, 1.2).\n\n| Element  | Correct                   | Wrong              |\n| -------- | ------------------------- | ------------------ |\n| Steps    | Step 1, Step 2, Step 3    | Step 1.5, Step 2.5 |\n| Phases   | PHASE 1, PHASE 2, PHASE 3 | PHASE 1.5, PHASE 2 |\n| Sections | ## 1. PURPOSE               | ## 1.1 PURPOSE     |\n\n**Sub-activities**: Use bullets within a step, not decimal sub-steps:\n```markdown\nStep 3: Execute workflow\n  - Load configuration\n  - Validate inputs  \n  - Run process\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. SECTION VOCABULARY\n\nCommands use two categories of notation: **semantic markers** (for blocking/validation states) and **section names** (for content organization).\n\n### Semantic Markers (Blocking/Validation)\n\nThese markers indicate workflow state and enforcement:\n\n| Marker | Name    | Purpose                     | Example Usage               |\n| ------ | ------- | --------------------------- | --------------------------- |\n| MANDATORY | Alert   | Critical/mandatory sections | `# MANDATORY PHASES`      |\n| PHASE  | Lock    | Phase/gate headers          | `## PHASE 1: INPUT`       |\n| PASSED | Check   | Passed/success status       | `PASSED`                   |\n| N/A    | Skip    | N/A or skipped              | `N/A (no memory files)`    |\n| STOP   | Stop    | Hard stop/blocking error    | `STOP - Phase incomplete`  |\n| WARNING| Warning | Non-blocking alert          | `VIOLATION DETECTED`       |\n| FAILED | Fail    | Validation failure          | `FAILED`                   |\n\n### Standard Section Names\n\nThese names identify section types. Use EXACTLY as shown:\n\n| Section      | H2 Format                    | Purpose                      |\n| ------------ | ---------------------------- | ---------------------------- |\n| PURPOSE      | `## N. PURPOSE`              | What the command does        |\n| CONTRACT     | `## N. CONTRACT`             | Inputs/outputs specification |\n| WORKFLOW     | `## N. WORKFLOW OVERVIEW`    | Process flow/steps table     |\n| INSTRUCTIONS | `## N. INSTRUCTIONS`         | How to execute               |\n| REFERENCE    | `## N. REFERENCE`            | Related resources            |\n| EXAMPLES     | `## N. EXAMPLES`             | Usage demonstrations         |\n| RELATED      | `## N. RELATED COMMANDS`     | Links to related commands    |\n| TOOLS        | `## N. TOOL SIGNATURES`      | MCP/tool configuration       |\n| ROUTING      | `## N. ARGUMENT ROUTING`     | Mode detection/dispatch      |\n| DOCS         | `## N. FULL DOCUMENTATION`   | Link to full docs            |\n| INPUT        | `## N. USER INPUT`           | User input display           |\n\n### Section Naming Rules\n\n1. **One name per purpose**: Don't reuse section names across different purposes\n2. **Consistent naming**: Use the same section name for the same purpose across commands\n3. **Exact format**: `## N. SECTION-NAME` (number, period, space, name in ALL CAPS)\n\n---\n\n## 7. FRONTMATTER REFERENCE\n\n### Required Fields\n\n```yaml\n---\ndescription: Clear, action-oriented single-line description shown in /help output. Start with action verb (Create, Search, Delete, Start, Stop).\n---\n```\n\n> **Important:** The `description` field MUST be a single-line string, not a YAML block scalar (`|` or `>`). Multi-line descriptions break `/help` output rendering.\n\n### Recommended Fields\n\n```yaml\n---\nargument-hint: \"<required> [optional] [--flag]\"\n# Format conventions:\n#   <angle-brackets> = required argument\n#   [square-brackets] = optional argument\n#   --flag = boolean flag\n#   [default: value] = argument with default\n\nallowed-tools: Tool1, Tool2, Tool3\n# Common tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob, Task\n# MCP tools: mcp__[server-name]__[tool_function]\n---\n```\n\n### Optional Fields\n\n```yaml\n---\nname: command-name\n# Override inferred name from filename\n\nmodel: opus\n# Override default model (USE SPARINGLY - only for complex reasoning)\n\nversion: 1.0.0\n# Track command version\n\ndisable-model-invocation: true\n# Prevent the AI agent from invoking this command\n---\n```\n\n### Example\n\n```yaml\n---\ndescription: Complete spec folder workflow (5 steps) - research through implementation\nargument-hint: \"<task> [:auto|:confirm]\"\nallowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Task\n---\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. MANDATORY GATE PATTERN (CRITICAL)\n\n### Why This Pattern Exists\n\nWithout this gate, AI agents may:\n- Infer tasks from conversation history or open files\n- Assume what the user wants based on screenshots or context\n- Proceed with incorrect assumptions instead of asking\n\n### When to Use\n\n| Argument Type                  | Use Mandatory Gate? | Example                              |\n| ------------------------------ | ------------------- | ------------------------------------ |\n| `<required>` (angle brackets)  | **YES**             | `<task>`, `<query>`, `<spec-folder>` |\n| `[optional]` (square brackets) | No (has default)    | `[count]`, `[--flag]`                |\n| `[:auto\\|:confirm]` mode flags | No (mode selection) | Mode suffixes only                   |\n\n### The Pattern\n\nAdd this block **immediately after frontmatter, before any other content**:\n\n```markdown\n# 🚨 MANDATORY FIRST ACTION - DO NOT SKIP\n\n**BEFORE READING ANYTHING ELSE IN THIS FILE, CHECK `$ARGUMENTS`:**\n\n\\`\\`\\`\nIF $ARGUMENTS is empty, undefined, or contains only whitespace (ignoring mode flags):\n    → STOP IMMEDIATELY\n    → Present the user with this question:\n        question: \"[Context-appropriate question]\"\n        options:\n          - label: \"[Action label]\"\n            description: \"[What user will provide]\"\n    → WAIT for user response\n    → Use their response as the [input type]\n    → Only THEN continue with this workflow\n\nIF $ARGUMENTS contains [expected input]:\n    → Continue reading this file\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**CRITICAL RULES:**\n- **DO NOT** infer [input type] from context, screenshots, or existing files\n- **DO NOT** assume what the user wants based on conversation history\n- **DO NOT** proceed past this point without an explicit [input] from the user\n- The [input] MUST come from `$ARGUMENTS` or user's answer to the question above\n```\n\n### Example Questions by Command Type\n\n| Command Purpose    | Question                                          |\n| ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------- |\n| Planning           | \"What would you like to plan?\"                    |\n| Research           | \"What topic would you like to research?\"          |\n| Implementation     | \"Which spec folder would you like to implement?\"  |\n| File improvement   | \"What would you like to improve and which files?\" |\n| Prompt enhancement | \"What prompt would you like to improve?\"          |\n| Generic routing    | \"What request would you like to route?\"           |\n\n### Multi-Phase Blocking Pattern\n\nFor commands requiring multiple inputs before workflow execution:\n\n```markdown\n# 🚨 MANDATORY PHASES - BLOCKING ENFORCEMENT\n\n> **HARD BLOCK**: Do not proceed past this section until ALL phases complete.\n\n## PHASE 1: INPUT COLLECTION\n[Collect required inputs from $ARGUMENTS or prompt user]\n\n## PHASE 2: CONTEXT VERIFICATION\n[Verify prerequisites exist]\n\n## PHASE STATUS VERIFICATION (BLOCKING)\n\n| Phase            | Status | Blocker? |\n| ---------------- | ------ | -------- |\n| Input Collection | ✅/❌   | HARD     |\n| Context Verify   | ✅/❌   | HARD     |\n\n**Gate Check:** ALL phases must show ✅. ANY ❌ = STOP and resolve.\n```\n\n### Violation Self-Detection\n\nEvery workflow command MUST include:\n\n```markdown\n## VIOLATION SELF-DETECTION (BLOCKING)\n\n**Before proceeding, verify you have NOT:**\n- [ ] Skipped any required phase\n- [ ] Used project tools before completing phases\n- [ ] Proceeded without required user confirmation\n\n**If ANY violation:** STOP → State violation → Return to phase → Complete properly\n```\n\n### Gate Exemption Declaration\n\nFor commands exempt from Gate 3:\n\n```markdown\n## GATE 3 STATUS: EXEMPT\n\n| Aspect      | Value                            |\n| ----------- | -------------------------------- |\n| Location    | [Where output goes]              |\n| Reason      | [Why exempt]                     |\n| Alternative | [What replaces spec folder]      |\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. SIMPLE COMMAND TEMPLATE\n\nUse for: Single-action commands with straightforward execution.\n\n```markdown\n---\ndescription: [Action verb] [what it does] [context/scope]\nargument-hint: \"<required-arg> [optional-arg]\"\nallowed-tools: Tool1, Tool2\n---\n\n# 🚨 MANDATORY FIRST ACTION - DO NOT SKIP\n\n**BEFORE READING ANYTHING ELSE IN THIS FILE, CHECK `$ARGUMENTS`:**\n\n\\`\\`\\`\nIF $ARGUMENTS is empty, undefined, or contains only whitespace:\n    → STOP IMMEDIATELY\n    → Present options to user\n    → WAIT for user response\n    → Only THEN continue\n\nIF $ARGUMENTS contains required input:\n    → Continue reading this file\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**CRITICAL RULES:**\n- **DO NOT** infer from context, screenshots, or conversation history\n- **DO NOT** assume what the user wants\n- **DO NOT** proceed without explicit input from the user\n\n---\n\n# [Command Title]\n\n[One sentence describing what this command does and when to use it.]\n\n---\n\n## 1. PURPOSE\n\n[2-3 sentences explaining the command's purpose and primary use case.]\n\n---\n\n## 2. CONTRACT\n\n**Inputs:** `$ARGUMENTS` — [Description of expected arguments]\n**Outputs:** `STATUS=<OK|FAIL> [ADDITIONAL_DATA=<value>]`\n\n---\n\n## 3. INSTRUCTIONS\n\nExecute the following steps:\n\n### Step 1: [Step Name]\n\n- [Sub-step or detail]\n- [Sub-step or detail]\n\n### Step 2: [Step Name]\n\n- [Sub-step or detail]\n\n### Step 3: Return Status\n\n- If successful: `STATUS=OK [DATA=<value>]`\n- If failed: `STATUS=FAIL ERROR=\"<message>\"`\n\n---\n\n## 4. EXAMPLE USAGE\n\n### Basic Usage\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\n/command-name \"argument\"\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n### With Optional Args\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\n/command-name \"argument\" --flag\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n---\n\n## 5. EXAMPLE OUTPUT\n\n\\`\\`\\`\n[Formatted output example]\n\nSTATUS=OK DATA=<value>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n---\n\n## 6. NOTES\n\n- **[Category]:** [Important note about usage]\n- **[Category]:** [Performance or limitation note]\n- **Requirements:** [Prerequisites or dependencies]\n```\n\n### Simple Command Example\n\n```yaml\n---\ndescription: Search codebase semantically using natural language queries\nargument-hint: \"<query> [--refined]\"\nallowed-tools: mcp__semantic-search__semantic_search\n---\n```\n\n---\n\n## 10. WORKFLOW COMMAND TEMPLATE\n\nUse for: Multi-step processes with defined phases and outputs.\n\n```markdown\n---\ndescription: [Workflow name] ([N] steps) - [brief purpose]\nargument-hint: \"<topic> [context]\"\nallowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Task\n---\n\n# 🚨 MANDATORY FIRST ACTION - DO NOT SKIP\n\n[Include mandatory gate pattern from Section 6]\n\n---\n\n# [Workflow Title]\n\n**Purpose**: [One sentence describing the workflow's goal and primary output.]\n\n---\n\n## 1. USER INPUT\n\n\\`\\`\\`text\n$ARGUMENTS\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n---\n\n## 2. WORKFLOW OVERVIEW ([N] STEPS)\n\n| Step | Name         | Purpose               | Outputs             |\n| ---- | ------------ | --------------------- | ------------------- |\n| 1    | [Step Name]  | [What it does]        | [Artifacts created] |\n| 2    | [Step Name]  | [What it does]        | [Artifacts created] |\n| 3    | [Step Name]  | [What it does]        | [Artifacts created] |\n| N    | Save Context | Preserve conversation | memory/*.md         |\n\n---\n\n## 3. INSTRUCTIONS\n\n### Step 1: [Step Name]\n\n[Detailed instructions for this step]\n\n**Validation checkpoint:**\n- [ ] [Condition that must be true]\n- [ ] [Another condition]\n\n### Step 2: [Step Name]\n\n[Detailed instructions for this step]\n\n---\n\n## 4. FAILURE RECOVERY\n\n| Failure Type        | Recovery Action  |\n| ------------------- | ---------------- |\n| [Failure condition] | [How to recover] |\n| [Another condition] | [Recovery steps] |\n\n---\n\n## 5. ERROR HANDLING\n\n| Condition          | Action                            |\n| ------------------ | --------------------------------- |\n| Empty `$ARGUMENTS` | Prompt user: \"Please describe...\" |\n| [Other condition]  | [Action to take]                  |\n\n---\n\n## 6. TEMPLATES USED\n\n- `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/templates/[template].md`\n- [Other template references]\n\n---\n\n## 7. COMPLETION REPORT\n\nAfter workflow completion, report:\n\n\\`\\`\\`\n✅ [Workflow Name] Complete\n\n[Summary of what was accomplished]\n\nArtifacts Created:\n- [artifact 1]\n- [artifact 2]\n\nNext Steps:\n- [Recommended follow-up action]\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n---\n\n## 8. EXAMPLES\n\n**Example 1: [Use case]**\n\\`\\`\\`\n/workflow-name [arguments]\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Example 2: [Another use case]**\n\\`\\`\\`\n/workflow-name [different arguments]\n\\`\\`\\`\n```\n\n---\n\n## 11. MODE-BASED COMMAND TEMPLATE\n\nUse for: Commands supporting `:auto` and `:confirm` execution modes.\n\n```markdown\n---\ndescription: [Workflow name] ([N] steps) - [purpose]. Supports :auto and :confirm modes\nargument-hint: \"<request> [:auto|:confirm]\"\nallowed-tools: Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Task\n---\n\n# 🚨 MANDATORY FIRST ACTION - DO NOT SKIP\n\n[Include mandatory gate pattern from Section 6]\n\n---\n\n# [Command Title]\n\n**Purpose**: [Description of what this command accomplishes.]\n\n---\n\n## 1. USER INPUT\n\n\\`\\`\\`text\n$ARGUMENTS\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n---\n\n## 2. MODE DETECTION & ROUTING\n\n### Step 1: Parse Mode Suffix\n\nDetect execution mode from command invocation:\n\n| Pattern                | Mode        | Behavior                                      |\n| ---------------------- | ----------- | --------------------------------------------- |\n| `/command:auto`        | AUTONOMOUS  | Execute all steps without user approval gates |\n| `/command:confirm`     | INTERACTIVE | Pause at each step for user approval          |\n| `/command` (no suffix) | PROMPT      | Ask user to choose mode                       |\n\n### Step 2: Mode Selection (when no suffix detected)\n\nIf no `:auto` or `:confirm` suffix is present, present options to user:\n\n**Question**: \"How would you like to execute this workflow?\"\n\n| Option | Mode        | Description                                                    |\n| ------ | ----------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **A**  | Autonomous  | Execute all steps without approval gates. Best for [use case]. |\n| **B**  | Interactive | Pause at each step for approval. Best for [use case].          |\n\n**Wait for user response before proceeding.**\n\n### Step 3: Transform Raw Input\n\nParse the raw text from `$ARGUMENTS` and transform into structured fields.\n\n---\n\n## 3. KEY BEHAVIORS\n\n### Autonomous Mode (`:auto`)\n- Executes all steps without user approval gates\n- Self-validates at each checkpoint\n- Makes informed decisions based on best judgment\n- Documents all significant decisions\n\n### Interactive Mode (`:confirm`)\n- Pauses after each step for user approval\n- Presents options: Approve, Review Details, Modify, Skip, Abort\n- Documents user decisions at each checkpoint\n- Allows course correction throughout workflow\n\n---\n\n## 4. CONTEXT LOADING\n\nWhen resuming work in an existing spec folder, prompt to load prior session memory:\n- **A)** Load most recent memory file (quick context refresh)\n- **B)** Load all recent files (up to 3) (comprehensive context)\n- **C)** List all files and select specific (historical search)\n- **D)** Skip (start fresh, no context)\n\n---\n\n## 5. EXAMPLES\n\n**Example 1: Autonomous execution**\n\\`\\`\\`\n/command:auto [arguments]\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Example 2: Interactive execution**\n\\`\\`\\`\n/command:confirm [arguments]\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n**Example 3: Prompt for mode selection**\n\\`\\`\\`\n/command [arguments]\n\\`\\`\\`\n```\n\n### Presentation / Router Split (Command Families)\n\nThe memory, speckit, create, doctor, and deep command families split each command into a **thin router** plus **owned assets**, so routing logic and presentation contracts evolve independently and long command files stay readable.\n\n**Common core — all split families:**\n\n| Asset | Owns |\n|-------|------|\n| `<command>.md` (thin router) | Mode resolution, owned-assets table, routing logic, and any Phase 0 / mandatory-input gate. Contains NO presentation content. |\n| `assets/<ns>_<command>_presentation.txt` | Startup prompts, dashboards and checkpoints, result templates, and next-step wording. The display source of truth. |\n\n- The router contains a **Presentation Boundary** section naming what lives only in the presentation asset; it must contain no inline startup-question wording, dashboard templates, or result templates. The split is behavior-preserving — relocate display content, never change routing semantics.\n- In `allowed-tools`, MCP tools use the fully-qualified `mcp__<server>__<tool>` form (e.g. `mcp__mk_spec_memory__memory_context`), matching the `opencode.json` MCP namespace. Bare tool IDs (e.g. `memory_context`) belong in instruction prose, never in `allowed-tools`.\n\n**Workflow-backed families (speckit, create, deep)** additionally own `:auto` / `:confirm` workflow YAML that the router routes modes to:\n\n| Asset | Owns |\n|-------|------|\n| `assets/<ns>_<command>_auto.yaml` | Autonomous-mode workflow: steps, agent dispatch, artifact writes. |\n| `assets/<ns>_<command>_confirm.yaml` | Interactive-mode workflow. |\n\nThe **memory** and **doctor** families have NO workflow YAML — their routers dispatch directly to tools and scripts.\n\n**Canonical router shape (first-class standard).** Every router uses one canonical, numbered section vocabulary — full integers, in this order: **`## 1. ROUTER CONTRACT`**, **`## 2. OWNED ASSETS`**, **`## 3. MODE ROUTING`**, **`## 4. EXECUTION TARGETS`**, **`## 5. PRESENTATION BOUNDARY`**, **`## 6. WORKFLOW SUMMARY`**. The blocking core is only `Owned Assets` + `Presentation Boundary`; the other four are recommended and surface as non-blocking warnings when absent. Variants differ by hand-off only, not by required sections:\n\n- **Workflow-YAML-backed** (speckit, create, deep-large) route modes into `_auto.yaml` / `_confirm.yaml`.\n- **Direct-dispatch-script** (memory, doctor, skill-benchmark) dispatch straight to tools and scripts and may leave the recommended sections as warnings.\n- **Compiled-stub** commands carry a `render-command-contract` marker and are exempt from section requirements (retained variant; no command currently uses it — the deep commands are full routers).\n\nDo not invent divergent synonyms (`Routing Assets`, `Workflow Routing`, `Execution Order`); the validator alias-normalizes those as a safety net, but the authored end state is the canonical names above. Reference shape: `.opencode/commands/speckit/plan.md` (router) + `speckit_plan_presentation.txt` (contract). Skeletons: [`command_router_template.md`](command_router_template.md), [`command_presentation_template.md`](command_presentation_template.md).\n\n---\n\n## 12. ARGUMENT DISPATCH PATTERN\n\nUse for: Commands that accept multiple argument types and need to route to different actions.\n\n### Pattern Overview\n\nWhen a single command handles multiple argument patterns (like `/semantic_search` accepting queries, actions, and flags), use an ASCII decision tree to document the routing logic clearly.\n\n### When to Use Argument Dispatch\n\n| Scenario                                   | Use Pattern?                 |\n| ------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------- |\n| Command has multiple action keywords       | **Yes**                      |\n| Command accepts both keywords AND queries  | **Yes**                      |\n| Command has only one action                | No (use simple template)     |\n| Command uses `:auto`/`:confirm` modes only | No (use mode-based template) |\n\n### The Pattern\n\n```markdown\n---\ndescription: [Command] with multiple entry points\nargument-hint: \"[action|query] [options]\"\nallowed-tools: [Tools]\n---\n\n# [Command Title]\n\n---\n\n## 1. ARGUMENT DISPATCH\n\n\\`\\`\\`\n$ARGUMENTS\n    │\n    ├─► Empty (no args)\n    │   └─► DEFAULT ACTION: [What happens with no args]\n    │\n    ├─► First word matches ACTION KEYWORD (case-insensitive)\n    │   ├─► \"start\" | \"on\" | \"init\"       → START ACTION\n    │   ├─► \"stop\" | \"off\" | \"kill\"       → STOP ACTION\n    │   ├─► \"status\" | \"info\"             → STATUS ACTION\n    │   ├─► \"search\" | \"find\" | \"query\"   → SEARCH ACTION (remaining args = query)\n    │   └─► \"reset\" | \"clear\"             → RESET ACTION\n    │\n    ├─► Looks like NATURAL LANGUAGE QUERY\n    │   Detection: 2+ words, question words, code terms, quotes\n    │   └─► SEARCH ACTION (full args = query)\n    │\n    └─► Single ambiguous word\n        └─► [DEFAULT ACTION] (assume most common intent)\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n---\n\n## 2. ACTION HANDLERS\n\n### START ACTION\n[Instructions for start]\n\n### STOP ACTION\n[Instructions for stop]\n\n### SEARCH ACTION\n[Instructions for search]\n\n---\n\n## 3. EXAMPLE ROUTING\n\n| Input                | Detected As      | Action                  |\n| -------------------- | ---------------- | ----------------------- |\n| (empty)              | No args          | Show menu/help          |\n| `start`              | Keyword          | START ACTION            |\n| `how does auth work` | Natural language | SEARCH ACTION           |\n| `oauth`              | Single word      | SEARCH ACTION (default) |\n```\n\n### Real Example: `/semantic_search`\n\n```\n/semantic_search [args]\n    │\n    ├─► No args\n    │   └─► Show usage help\n    │\n    ├─► \"index\" | \"reindex\" | \"rebuild\"\n    │   └─► INDEX ACTION: Rebuild vector index\n    │\n    ├─► \"status\" | \"health\"\n    │   └─► STATUS ACTION: Show index health\n    │\n    ├─► Natural language query (2+ words)\n    │   └─► SEARCH ACTION: Execute semantic search\n    │\n    └─► Single ambiguous word\n        └─► SEARCH ACTION (assume search intent)\n```\n\n### Combining with Mode-Based Pattern\n\nFor commands that need BOTH argument dispatch AND mode support:\n\n```\n$ARGUMENTS\n    │\n    ├─► Parse mode suffix (:auto | :confirm)\n    │\n    └─► After mode extraction, dispatch remaining args:\n        ├─► \"action1\" → ACTION 1\n        ├─► \"action2\" → ACTION 2\n        └─► Natural language → DEFAULT ACTION\n```\n\n---\n\n## 13. DESTRUCTIVE COMMAND TEMPLATE\n\nUse for: Commands that delete data or make irreversible changes.\n\n```markdown\n---\ndescription: [Action] (DESTRUCTIVE)\nargument-hint: \"[--confirm]\"\nallowed-tools: Bash\n---\n\n# [Command Title]\n\n**DESTRUCTIVE OPERATION** - [Brief warning about what will be affected.]\n\n---\n\n## 1. PURPOSE\n\n[Explain the destructive action and why it might be needed.]\n\n---\n\n## 2. CONTRACT\n\n**Inputs:** `$ARGUMENTS` — Must include `--confirm` flag to skip prompt\n**Outputs:** `STATUS=<OK|FAIL|CANCELLED> ACTION=<action|cancelled>`\n\n---\n\n## 3. INSTRUCTIONS\n\n### Step 1: Safety Check - Require Confirmation\n\n- Check if `--confirm` flag is present in `$ARGUMENTS`\n- If NOT present:\n  - Ask user: \"[Warning message]. Are you sure?\"\n  - Options: \"Yes, proceed\" / \"No, cancel\"\n  - If user cancels: `STATUS=CANCELLED ACTION=cancelled`\n\n### Step 2: Show What Will Be Affected\n\n- Display current state\n- List items that will be deleted/changed\n- Show size/count of affected data\n\n### Step 3: Execute Destructive Action\n\n- [Step-by-step execution]\n- Log each action taken\n\n### Step 4: Verify Completion\n\n- Confirm action completed\n- Show new state\n\n### Step 5: Provide Recovery Guidance\n\n- Explain how to rebuild/restore if needed\n- Link to relevant commands\n\n### Step 6: Return Status\n\n- If completed: `STATUS=OK ACTION=[action]`\n- If cancelled: `STATUS=CANCELLED ACTION=cancelled`\n- If failed: `STATUS=FAIL ERROR=\"<message>\"`\n\n---\n\n## 4. EXAMPLE USAGE\n\n### Without Confirmation (Safe Default)\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\n/command-name\n\\`\\`\\`\n→ Will prompt for confirmation before proceeding\n\n### With Confirmation Flag (Skip Prompt)\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\n/command-name --confirm\n\\`\\`\\`\n→ Proceeds immediately (use with caution)\n\n---\n\n## 5. NOTES\n\n- **When to Use:**\n  - [Valid use case 1]\n  - [Valid use case 2]\n\n- **Impact:**\n  - [What will be lost]\n  - [Other consequences]\n  - [What is preserved]\n  - [Recovery options]\n\n- **Alternatives to Consider:**\n  - [Less destructive alternative]\n  - [Another option]\n\n---\n\n## 6. SAFETY FEATURES\n\n- Requires explicit confirmation by default\n- Shows what will be affected before proceeding\n- Provides clear recovery steps\n- Cannot accidentally affect [protected items]\n```\n\n---\n\n## 14. NAMESPACE COMMAND PATTERN\n\nUse for: Grouping related commands under a common prefix.\n\n### Directory Structure\n\n```\n.opencode/commands/\n└── [namespace]/           # Directory name = namespace\n    ├── [action1].md       # → /namespace:action1\n    ├── [action2].md       # → /namespace:action2\n    └── [action3].md       # → /namespace:action3\n```\n\n### Example: Index Namespace\n\n```\n.opencode/commands/\n└── index/\n    ├── start.md     → /index:start\n    ├── stop.md      → /index:stop\n    ├── search.md    → /index:search\n    ├── stats.md     → /index:stats\n    ├── history.md   → /index:history\n    └── reset.md     → /index:reset\n```\n\n### Naming Conventions\n\n| Element             | Convention             | Example                      |\n| ------------------- | ---------------------- | ---------------------------- |\n| Namespace directory | lowercase, hyphen-case | `index/`, `git-workflow/`    |\n| Action files        | lowercase, hyphen-case | `search.md`, `full-reset.md` |\n| Resulting command   | namespace:action       | `/index:search`              |\n\n---\n\n## 15. VALIDATION CHECKLIST\n\nBefore publishing a command, verify:\n\n### Frontmatter\n\n- [ ] `description` is present and action-oriented\n- [ ] `argument-hint` shows expected format (if args expected)\n- [ ] `allowed-tools` lists all tools used (if any)\n- [ ] No angle brackets `< >` in description (reserved for hints)\n\n### Mandatory Gate (CRITICAL for required arguments)\n\n- [ ] If `argument-hint` contains `<required>` args → **MANDATORY GATE present**\n- [ ] Gate is **immediately after frontmatter**, before any other content\n- [ ] Gate presents options to user with appropriate question\n- [ ] Gate includes all 4 CRITICAL RULES (DO NOT infer, assume, proceed)\n- [ ] Skip gate only if ALL arguments are `[optional]` with defaults\n\n### Structure\n\n- [ ] H1 title matches command purpose\n- [ ] H2 sections use format: `## N. SECTION-NAME` (see Section 6 for section vocabulary)\n- [ ] H3 subsections: `### Step N: Description`\n- [ ] Dividers (`---`) between major sections\n- [ ] Instructions are numbered and actionable\n- [ ] Example usage shows 2-3 scenarios\n- [ ] Full integer step numbering only (no 1.5, 2.5 - see Section 5)\n\n### Header Format\n\n- [ ] H1: Plain title only (`# Command Title`) or with semantic emoji for blocking sections (`# 🚨 MANDATORY PHASES`)\n- [ ] H2: Numbered + SECTION-NAME (`## 1. PURPOSE`)\n- [ ] H3/H4: Title case (`### Step 1: Description`)\n- [ ] Consistent numbering (1, 2, 3...)\n- [ ] Section names from approved vocabulary (Section 6)\n\n**Blocking Phase Pattern:**\nCommands with mandatory input phases use these semantic markers:\n- `# MANDATORY PHASES` - Critical blocking section (H1)\n- `## PHASE N:` - Required blocking phases (H2)\n- `## PHASE STATUS VERIFICATION` - Gate checks (H2)\n- `## VIOLATION SELF-DETECTION` - Violation recovery (H2)\n\n---\n\n## 16. ORCHESTRATOR + WORKERS PATTERN\n\nUse for: Commands that spawn parallel sub-agents for exploration/analysis.\n\n```\nOPUS ORCHESTRATOR → Dispatches → SONNET WORKERS (parallel)\n     │                              │\n     └── Synthesizes ←──────────────┘\n```\n\n| Role             | Model    | Responsibility                                        |\n| ---------------- | -------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Orchestrator** | `opus`   | Task understanding, dispatch, verification, synthesis |\n| **Workers**      | `sonnet` | Fast parallel exploration, hypothesis generation      |\n\n**Use when**: Parallel codebase exploration, multi-aspect analysis, complex planning.\n**Skip when**: Simple single-action commands, sequential workflows.\n\n---\n\n## 17. STATUS OUTPUT PATTERNS\n\n### Standard Patterns\n\n| Pattern                                 | Use Case       | Example              |\n| --------------------------------------- | -------------- | -------------------- |\n| `STATUS=OK`                             | Simple success | Basic commands       |\n| `STATUS=OK RESULTS_COUNT=N`             | Search/query   | `/index:search`      |\n| `STATUS=OK ACTION=<action>`             | State change   | `/index:start`       |\n| `STATUS=OK ACTION=<action> PATH=<path>` | File creation  | `/speckit:complete` |\n| `STATUS=FAIL ERROR=\"<message>\"`         | All failures   | Error handling       |\n| `STATUS=CANCELLED ACTION=cancelled`     | User abort     | Interactive commands |\n\n---\n\n## 18. BEST PRACTICES SUMMARY\n\n### DO\n\n| Practice                                 | Reason                            |\n| ---------------------------------------- | --------------------------------- |\n| Include mandatory gate for required args | Prevents context inference errors |\n| Use action verbs in descriptions         | Clear, scannable in /help         |\n| Document all steps with checkpoints      | Enables debugging and recovery    |\n| Provide example usage                    | Users learn faster                |\n| Return structured status                 | Enables automation                |\n| Use appropriate command type             | Right tool for the job            |\n\n### DON'T\n\n| Anti-Pattern               | Problem                      |\n| -------------------------- | ---------------------------- |\n| Skip mandatory gate        | AI will infer incorrectly    |\n| Vague descriptions         | Users won't know when to use |\n| Missing error handling     | Failures become mysterious   |\n| No examples                | Users struggle to start      |\n| Inconsistent status format | Breaks automation            |\n| Over-complex commands      | Split into namespace instead |\n\n---\n\n## 19. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n### Templates\n- [frontmatter_templates.md](../../../shared/assets/frontmatter_templates.md) - Frontmatter by document type\n- [skill_md_template.md](../../../create-skill/assets/skill/skill_md_template.md) - If converting to skill\n\n### Standards\n- [core_standards.md](../../../shared/references/core_standards.md) - Document type rules\n- [validation.md](../../../shared/references/validation.md) - Quality scoring","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":1232,"totalLines":1232,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_template.md","time":{"start":1784180579807,"end":1784180579846}},"id":"prt_f69731dd4001o9YIzs3IcnC1SM","sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","messageID":"msg_f6972d97f001vFSaaIbVo79G3z"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784180579886,"sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"call_5b40e75b99c544b2849a4934","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"echo \"===010 contents===\"; ls -R /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/010-scorecard-and-closeout/ 2>/dev/null | head -50; echo \"===011 contents===\"; ls -R /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/011-create-benchmark-completeness-remediation/ 2>/dev/null | head -50"},"output":"===010 contents===\ndescription.json\ngraph-metadata.json\nplan.md\nspec.md\ntasks.md\n===011 contents===\nchecklist.md\ndescription.json\nevidence\ngraph-metadata.json\nimplementation-summary.md\nplan.md\nspec.md\ntasks.md\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/011-create-benchmark-completeness-remediation//evidence:\nreview-fable.md\nreview-sol-ultra-rereview.md\nreview-sol-ultra.md\n","metadata":{"output":"===010 contents===\ndescription.json\ngraph-metadata.json\nplan.md\nspec.md\ntasks.md\n===011 contents===\nchecklist.md\ndescription.json\nevidence\ngraph-metadata.json\nimplementation-summary.md\nplan.md\nspec.md\ntasks.md\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/011-create-benchmark-completeness-remediation//evidence:\nreview-fable.md\nreview-sol-ultra-rereview.md\nreview-sol-ultra.md\n","exit":0,"truncated":false},"title":"echo \"===010 contents===\"; ls -R /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/010-scorecard-and-closeout/ 2>/dev/null | head -50; echo \"===011 contents===\"; ls -R /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/011-create-benchmark-completeness-remediation/ 2>/dev/null | head -50","time":{"start":1784180579865,"end":1784180579882}},"id":"prt_f69731de0001zM2EXq1kozSzBt","sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","messageID":"msg_f6972d97f001vFSaaIbVo79G3z"}}
