{"type":"text","timestamp":1784181704094,"sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","part":{"id":"prt_f69844557001zYA3zBDRIEFEth","messageID":"msg_f6982a15b001NP1cZEOU0wDzPO","sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","type":"text","text":"Strong RQ4 evidence (claude mirror empty, `$ARGUMENTS` echo drift, subaction style unnamed). Writing iteration 4.","time":{"start":1784181704023,"end":1784181704093}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784181704097,"sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"call_2ae980a7339d47989bd46e02","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Iteration 4: RQ4 — router/dispatch-logic improvements\n\n## Focus\nArgument-hint grammar, `$ARGUMENTS`/positional handling, `:auto`/`:confirm` resolution completeness, and dual-runtime (opencode/codex/claude) parity. Identify where the canon is silent and the corpus drifts, and propose canon + check deltas per gap.\n\n## Findings\n\n### F4.1 — `User request: $ARGUMENTS` raw echo is an undocumented, inconsistent dispatch idiom\n14 commands append a bare `User request: $ARGUMENTS` line at the end of the router body: all 11 `create/*` commands plus `doctor/mcp.md`, `doctor/update.md:63`, `doctor/speckit.md`. No speckit/deep/memory/design router does this. The create-command canon never specifies this idiom — it defines `$ARGUMENTS` parsing (SKILL.md:225-231, command_template.md:50-61) but never sanctions a trailing raw echo, and the router template skeleton (command_router_template.md:53-104) has no such line. The idiom exists to inject the user's raw input into the workflow YAML's context, but because it is undocumented it appears in exactly the create family (likely copied from a seed) and nowhere else — a textbook prose-drift/vector for inconsistency.\n\n[SOURCE: corpus scan `User request: $ARGUMENTS`, 2026-07-16 — 14 files]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/commands/doctor/update.md:63]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/assets/command_router_template.md:53-104]\n\n**Candidate delta C4.1:** Canon: in create-command SKILL.md Step 9/Step 11 + `command_router_template.md` MODE ROUTING, document the **input-injection contract** — either (a) standardize `User request: $ARGUMENTS` as the router→YAML handoff and require it on all workflow-YAML routers, or (b) deprecate it in favor of the YAML reading `$ARGUMENTS` from its own dispatch context (removing the echo). Pick (b) to keep the router thin and remove a duplicated-input vector. Check: warn (P2) when a workflow-YAML router carries a raw `$ARGUMENTS` echo that the canon has deprecated, OR when a router consumes `$ARGUMENTS` in a way not declared in `argument-hint`. Acceptance: the 14 echoes are reconciled to one documented contract; a router echoing an undeclared positional warns.\n\n### F4.2 — \"Three-runtime parity\" is actually two-runtime (opencode↔codex); claude has no command mirror\nRQ4 and 066/spec.md:71-74 imply opencode/codex/claude command parity. In practice only the Codex mirror exists: `.codex/prompts/` holds 38 synced prompt files generated by `sync-prompts.cjs` (`:12` `OUTPUT_DIR = .codex/prompts`; `:75` \"Codex runtime entry point\"). `.claude/commands/` exists but contains **0** command files. So the create-command canon's implicit three-runtime parity claim is unmet for Claude, and no canon rule states which runtime mirrors are required or how a command advertises runtime availability. This is a dispatch-logic parity gap: a command authored \"canonically\" is invisible to the Claude runtime with no signal to the author.\n\n[SOURCE: .codex/prompts (38 files) vs .claude/commands (0 files), 2026-07-16]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/codex/sync-prompts.cjs:12,75,121-128]\n\n**Candidate delta C4.2:** Canon: add a \"Runtime mirror\" subsection to create-command SKILL.md stating the parity contract — which runtimes are mirrored, by which sync tool, and that command authors must not hand-author mirror files (the codex mirror is generated, per sync-prompts.cjs:164). If Claude parity is intended, either wire a claude sync or explicitly scope parity to opencode+codex and correct the canon/benchmark wording. Check: extend `sync-prompts.cjs` parity gate to assert the declared runtime set; warn when a command's `description`/`argument-hint` references a runtime feature the active mirrors don't support. Acceptance: the parity surface is documented; a command claiming `:auto` has its mirror generated or the gap is explicit.\n\n### F4.3 — Mode-resolution completeness is unchecked (`:auto`/`:confirm` hint vs both execution targets)\n30 commands declare `:auto`/`:confirm` in `argument-hint`. The 066 adapter S2 checks that referenced assets *exist* (target reachability) but does not check **mode-resolution completeness**: that a hint advertising `:auto` and `:confirm` has EXECUTION TARGETS rows for both modes and that both `_auto.yaml` and `_confirm.yaml` (for workflow-YAML routers) are present and targeted. A command could declare `:auto` in its hint, ship only `_confirm.yaml`, and pass every existing check while silently failing autonomous mode. The create-command canon states the MODE ROUTING pattern (SKILL.md:303-316) but never makes hint↔target completeness a rule.\n\n[SOURCE: corpus scan — 30 commands declare :auto/:confirm]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-alignment/scripts/adapters/sk-doc-command.cjs:374-382 (S2 reachability only)]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/SKILL.md:303-316]\n\n**Candidate delta C4.3:** Canon: add a \"mode completeness\" rule to SKILL.md Step 10 — every mode suffix in `argument-hint` must have a matching EXECUTION TARGETS row and, for workflow-YAML routers, a matching `_<mode>.yaml` asset. Check: a `mode_resolution_complete` check (P1) that, for each `:<mode>` token in the hint, asserts an EXECUTION TARGETS row naming that mode and (workflow-YAML variant) the corresponding asset path. Acceptance: a workflow-YAML router whose hint lists `:auto` but lacks `_auto.yaml` or an `:auto` EXECUTION TARGETS row flags P1; speckit/plan (has both) exits clean.\n\n### F4.4 — Subaction-dispatch direct-router style is unnamed; positional `$1..$N` is undefined and unused\nThe memory family (esp. `.opencode/commands/memory/search.md`, `manage.md`) uses a **subaction argument-dispatch** style: a hint like `\"<query> | preflight <specFolder> <taskId> | postflight … | causal <memoryId> …\"` routes to distinct EXECUTION TARGETS via a first-token classifier (`search.md:21,48` uses `ARGS_PRESENT`/`QUERY` + a known-subcommand check). This is the 066 \"subaction router\" topology, but the create-command canon's dispatch patterns (SKILL.md:288-300 \"Argument Dispatch\", command_template.md:849-961) describe a generic ASCII tree and never name this memory-style first-token subaction routing as a first-class form, nor define how hint positionals (`<specFolder> <taskId>`) bind to named router variables. Separately, the canon mentions `$1..$N` positional handling in RQ4 framing, but the corpus uses **only** the whole-string `$ARGUMENTS` — no command uses `$1`/`$2` positionals, so any `$N` contract is aspirational and undefined.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/commands/memory/search.md:11-54]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/SKILL.md:288-300]\n[SOURCE: corpus scan — zero `$1`/`$2` positional usage]\n\n**Candidate delta C4.4:** Canon: (a) add a \"Subaction argument-dispatch router\" subsection to SKILL.md Step 9/11 naming the memory-style first-token routing (`ARGS_PRESENT` + first-token classifier → named variables), with memory/search as the reference; (b) explicitly define the positional contract — either document `$1..$N` binding (and add a check) or state that positionals are accessed only via `$ARGUMENTS` whole-string parsing and remove the `$N` implication. Recommend (b)-whole-string. Check: warn (P2) when a hint declares multiple `<positional>` tokens but the router body does not show how each binds. Acceptance: memory/search is classifiable canonically; a multi-positional hint without documented binding warns.\n\n### F4.5 — argument-hint grammar has no binding contract (hint tokens ↔ router variables)\nThe argument-hint grammar (`<>` required, `[]` optional, `--flag`) is purely lexical (SKILL.md:211-214). There is no rule mapping hint tokens to the variables a router/YAML consumes. `speckit/plan.md:3` lists `--phases`, `--phase-names`, `--phase-folder`, `--level`, `--start-state`, etc., but nothing guarantees the `_auto.yaml` reads those exact names, so hint↔workflow drift is uncatchable structurally. This generalizes F4.1/F4.4: the hint is a free-text surface with no machine-checkable contract to dispatch.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-command/SKILL.md:211-214]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/commands/speckit/plan.md:3,31-38]\n\n**Candidate delta C4.5:** Canon: define a \"hint binding\" convention — `--flag` tokens in `argument-hint` should correspond to setup variables consumed by the EXECUTION TARGETS / workflow YAML (e.g. `--phases` → `phases` setup var). Check (P2, heuristic): for workflow-YAML routers, cross-reference `--<flag>` tokens in the hint against setup-var names declared in the EXECUTION TARGETS setup step (e.g. `update.md:43` binds `force`,`no_snapshot`,…); warn on unbound flags. Acceptance: a hint flag with no matching setup-var binding warns; doctor/update (fully bound) exits clean.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n- Corpus scans: `User request: $ARGUMENTS` (14 files); `:auto` count (30); `$1`/`$2` (0); `.codex/prompts` (38) vs `.claude/commands` (0).\n- Canon: SKILL.md:211-214,225-231,288-316; command_router_template.md:53-104; command_template.md:50-61,849-961.\n- Adapter: sk-doc-command.cjs:374-382; sync-prompts.cjs:12,75,121-128,164.\n- Corpus routers: memory/search.md:11-54; doctor/update.md:43,63; speckit/plan.md:3,31-38.\n\n## Assessment\n- **newInfoRatio: 0.8** — RQ4 surfaces four net-new dispatch-logic gaps (raw-echo idiom, claude-mirror absence, mode-completeness, hint-binding) plus the subaction-style naming; F4.2 (claude mirror empty) and F4.3 (mode completeness) are high-value structural findings.\n- **Novelty justification:** The claude-mirror emptiness inverts the assumed three-runtime parity to two-runtime; the mode-completeness gap shows a real silent-failure path no instrument catches.\n- **Confidence:** high on F4.1/F4.2/F4.3 (measured); medium-high on F4.4/F4.5 (style/binding gaps; heuristics proposed).\n- **Partial RQ4 answer:** five dispatch-logic deltas (C4.1–C4.5); the highest-priority are C4.2 (document/scope runtime parity) and C4.3 (mode-completeness check).\n\n## Reflection\n- **What worked:** Checking the *actual* mirror directories instead of trusting canon prose — revealed claude parity is unmet. Counting `$1`/`$2` usage — disproved the positional assumption cheaply.\n- **What failed / ruled out:** The first `$ARGUMENTS` family grep misfired on glob quoting; the literal-string re-grep recovered the precise 14-file set.\n- **Ruled out:** \"Add `$1..$N` positional support\" — no command uses it and it adds complexity; rule out in favor of whole-string `$ARGUMENTS` + documented subaction binding (C4.4).\n- **Recommended next focus (RQ5):** Authoring ergonomics — consolidate the recurring authoring failures (fat monolith hints, missing loader-gating frontmatter, prose drift between a command and its guides/presentation) into template/logic changes, and cross-cut the C1.x–C4.x deltas into a prioritized backlog.\n","filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/012-command-improvement-research/research/lineages/glm52-max/iterations/iteration-004.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/012-command-improvement-research/research/lineages/glm52-max/iterations/iteration-004.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/system-deep-loop/066-command-surface-benchmark/012-command-improvement-research/research/lineages/glm52-max/iterations/iteration-004.md","time":{"start":1784181704093,"end":1784181704096}},"id":"prt_f6984459a001NY8HphzPoC9lES","sessionID":"ses_0968f2113ffehJfWsGHuGr12Oc","messageID":"msg_f6982a15b001NP1cZEOU0wDzPO"}}
